<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgian President Visits NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Georgia is interested in closer
ties with NATO through the Partnership for Peace (PfP) program,
but opposes the expansion of the alliance, President Eduard
Shevardnadze said here today.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Georgian president made the remarks after a
meeting with NATO Secretary General Javier Solana on bilateral
relations and the mechanisms of the PfP.
</P>
<P>
"The relationship between NATO and Georgia is being absolutely
normalized," said Shevardnadze who arrived here today.
</P>
<P>
Asked about Georgia's opposition to NATO's expansion,
Shevardnadze said: "As far as the enlargement is concerned, it
should be effected in such a way that it should not lead us to a
new type of confrontation."
</P>
<P>
"Of great importance, I think, will be the intensification and
deepening of cooperation between NATO and Russia," he added.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that NATO hopes to cooperate with Georgia
"bilaterally and regionally" and that he will visit Georgia as
soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
