<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechen Separatist Leader Dudayev Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Chechen separatist leader
Dzhokhar Dudayev has been killed during a missile strike from
Russian troops, the Itar-Tass news agency reported this evening.
</P>
<P>
It quotd Dudayev's government as saying that he was killed
on the night from April 21 to 22 near the village of Gekhi Chu,
some 30 kilometers southwest of the Chechen capital of Grozny,
after the missile strike.
</P>
<P>
The Dudayev government's statement on his death was
reportedly delivered to the Itar-Tass office in Grozny by the
former leader of the Dudayev delegation to the 1995 negotiations
with Moscow, Khozh-Akhmed Yarikhanov.
</P>
<P>
"Dudayev is dead, there is no doubt about it," Yarikhanov
stated.
</P>
<P>
State-run television stations here have confirmed the reports
on Dudayev's death.
</P>
<P>
Some of Dudayev's closest associates reportedly died together
with the Chechen separatist leader.
</P>
<P>
Dudayev, 51, had been at the head of the Chechen separatist
movement since the break-up of the Soviet Union in 1991. For the
past 16 months, he had led armed resistance to the Russian troops
which operated in the local republic to preserve Russia's
territorial integrity against armed Chechen separatists.
</P>
<P>
However, the reports about Dudayev's death have been disputed
by a number of sources, and the Grozny-based pro-Moscow
government of Chechnya has begun checking out the facts. Russian
military sources said they had no immediate information about
the alleged rocketing of Gekhi Chu on April 21-22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
