<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Satisfied with Missile Talks with DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
expressed satisfaction with the first round of missile talks with
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department deputy spokesman Glyn Davies told a press
briefing that the two-day talks in Berlin on Saturday and Sunday
were useful and set a good beginning for further talks between the
two sides on the missile issue.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government is interested in continuing the
discussions, Davies said, adding that the U.S. goal is to
encourage DPRK to join a multilateral group seeking to curb the
international missile trade.
</P>
<P>
Despite repeated denials by Pyongyong, Washington has been
alleging that DPRK has sold long-range Scud missiles to Iran and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government would like to have a DPRK commitment to
stop both the export and production of missiles, Davies said.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin talks, the first of its kind between Washington and
Pyongyong, were sponsored by the U.S. side.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman noted that the talks were unrelated to
the latest proposal by the United States and South Korea to hold a
four-way talks on the future of the Korean Peninsula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
