<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Farm Debt to Hit 10-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Business-related farm debt in
the U.S. is likely to hit a 10-year record but remain far under
the peak set in 1984, the U.S. Agriculture Department (USDA)
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Farm debt is expected to reach 154.6 billion U.S. dollars by
the end of the year and that would be the sixth increase in seven
years following five straight years in which payoffs exceeded new
loans, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
"Continued economic growth, high grain prices, expanded acreage
for some crops and stable farm incomes are behind much of this
year's expected expansion," the USDA concluded.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, total farm debt at the end of 1996 is expected to
be 20 percent below the 1984 record. In percentage terms, the USDA
added, debt increases in the 1990s remain well under levels of the
1970s, when debt grew by more than 10 percent each year.
</P>
<P>
Little growth is expected in borrowing for real estate this
year and the increase will be caused by new loans for equipment
and purposes other than real estate. Even so, more and more of the
demand for credit for equipment and machinery is being met by
dealers through a combination of leasing and trade credit.
</P>
<P>
Most commercial farm-credit lenders are expected to be strong
financially this year, the USDA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
