<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepalese Forfeits Savings in Indian Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Many Nepalese citizens having
deposit accounts in various banks in an Indian border city have
forfeited their savings, Nepal's official news agency RSS said
today.
</P>
<P>
The exact amount seized by the Indian Income Tax Department
from these banks and the number of Nepalese depositors losing
their money were yet to be known, but it was estimated that about
1,300 Nepalese had forfeited around four million Indian rupees
(more than 100,000 US dollars) in the State Bank of India in the
Indian city of Jogbani near the border.
</P>
<P>
According to RSS, Nepalese businessmen, politicians and social
workers living in the eastern Morang district often have saving
accounts in banks in bordering Indian towns.
</P>
<P>
Even the Nepalese people working in India and former Gorkha
soldiers who had served in Indian army had lost their money, RSS
said.
</P>
<P>
An existing Nepal-India treaty prescribes forfeiture of the
property possessed by Nepalese and Indian citizens in each other's
countries, but the same treaty prohibits India from applying its
income tax act to Nepalese depositors, it added.
</P>
<P>
An Indian bank officer, quoted by RSS, said that many Nepalese
deposit their money in Indian banks for fear of possible
devaluation of the Nepalese rupee against Indian rupee.
</P>
<P>
The problem arose because the Nepalese account holders did not
fill a special form in accordance with an Indian foreign exchange
regulation act, it was said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
