<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Falls in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit dropped
by 17.1 percent in February to 8.2 billion U.S. dollars from a
revised January deficit of 9.9 billion dollars, the Commerce
Department said today.
</P>
<P>
Exports of goods rose 1.4 percent to 49.7 billion dollars in
February, the second best showing on record, while exports of
services went up 3.3 percent to 18.4 billion dollars, an all-time
high.
</P>
<P>
The marked increase in exports of goods was due to a rise of
743 million dollars in sales of civilian aircraft, a 108-million-
dollar increase in the sale of American tobacco products abroad
and a gain of 102 million dollars in sales of oil drilling
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Imports of goods declined 0.9 percent to 63.5 billion dollars
while imports of services rose by 1.4 percent to 12.8 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The decline in imports was due to a 156-million-dollar drop in
shipments of foreign computer chips and a 22-million-dollar
decrease in imports of foreign cars.
</P>
<P>
But car exports dropped by 70 million dollars to 5.3 billion
dollars in the month, leaving the U.S. deficit in cars and car
parts at 5.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Another big deficit category, oil imports, declined 13.8
percent to 3.64 billion dollars, the smallest monthly figure since
last October.
</P>
<P>
Even with the monthly improvement, the deficit for the first
two months of 1996 is running at an annual rate of 108.4 billion
dollars, only 3.1 billion dollars less than the 111.5 billion
dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. trade deficit with Japan rose 2.7 percent in February
to 3.9 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
