<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Economic Growth Slows Down This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The economic growth rate of Germany
will be less than 1 percent this year, instead of the 1.5 percent
forecast earlier, Minister of Economics Guenter Rexrodt said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting of the Free Democratic Party, Rexrodt
said the economic situation in the latter half of the year will be
better than the first half, adding that the growth rate in 1997
can reach 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Theo Waigel agreed that the present
economic slowdown is not a recession, but a temporary weakness.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, businessmen are more pessimistic. The Federation
of German Industries said a recession is still possible. Though
interest rates were cut again recently, the public doubt whether
there will be any growth at all.
</P>
<P>
The federation also urges the government to control wage rises.
</P>
<P>
A survey of 431 enterprises shows that the present economic
situation is worse than last fall. Investment and orders are
slipping, and there are again more companies firing than hiring
workers since 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
