<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Shortage Affects Mongolia's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia's oil reserves this
year have dropped to the lowest level in recent years and the
shortage of oil will cause difficulty to the country's economic
development, Mongolian businessmen warned.
</P>
<P>
The warning came from officials of the Mongolian Oil Import and
Export Corporation, the country's biggest state-run oil supplier,
in a letter to the State Great Hural (the country's parliament)
and government.
</P>
<P>
The officials of the corporation blamed the oil shortage on the
government's restrictions on the prices of oil products.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, they asked the Great Hural and the government to
lift the restrictions and allocate more money to increasing the
reserves of oil products, which would guarantee the normal
operation and security of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
They complained in the letter that the government's decision in
1994 to fix the prices of oil products in an effort to control
inflation had brought great losses to the corporation.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 alone, the corporation suffered a loss of 2.3 billion
tugriks (about 5.75 million U.S. dollars) because of the decision.
</P>
<P>
As Mongolia is not capable of turning out oil products itself
at present, the corporation's operation has a direct bearing on
the development of the country's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
