<HEADLINE> French Foreign Minister Leaves Damascus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Harve de
Charette left here this afternoon, concluding his visit to Syria
aimed at pushing a French initiative to end the conflict in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, de Charette met with Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad and his Syrian counterpart Farouq al-Shara to
discuss the present efforts undertaken by the parties concerned to
find a way out of the Lebanese crisis and ways of safeguarding
civilians.
</P>
<P>
De Charette described his talks with al-Shara as "useful"
before his departure.
</P>
<P>
France has offered a three-step plan to resolve the Lebanese
crisis: securing a ceasefire, making security arrangements capable
of protecting civilians and resuming the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The French initiative found support in Syria, Lebanon and Iran,
whereas, Israel rejected it. Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres
preferred the U.S. mediation, and criticized the plurality of
diplomatic drives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
