<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increased Tax Revenues in China in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China took in 133.3 billion yuan
in industrial and commercial taxes in the first quarter of this
year, about 28 percent more than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
This represents about 22 percent of the total expected this
year.
</P>
<P>
Tax paid to the central treasury rose about 29 percent to 72
billion yuan, that to the local level were up about 27 percent to
61.3 billion yuan, and import tariffs levied by customs went up by
nearly 50 percent to 11.4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Domestic value-added taxes increased by about 25 percent to
61.7 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Industrial and commercial taxes mostly grew at different rates
in different places. In Ningbo and Qingdao, two port cities in
east China, in southwest China's Guizhou Province, and in
northwest China Shaanxi and Gansu provinces and Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region taxes rose by more than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that stable economic growth has broadened tax
sources this year when industrial output expanded by 13.6 percent
and tax administrations nationwide took in 3.47 billion yuan in
back taxes, 2.8 times the amount collected in the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Xiang Huaicheng, deputy director of the State Administration of
Taxation, has said that effective steps should be taken to ensure
that more of the local taxes get collected.
</P>
<P>
China's local taxes have increased by more than 30 percent for
two years in a row, and individual income taxes, as part of local
taxes, rose by nearly 81 percent to a record 13.1 billion yuan in
1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
