<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ban Likely to Be Lifted Next Week: UK Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- British Agriculture Minister
Douglas Hogg has expressed the hope that the worldwide ban on
British beef exports imposed by the European Union (EU) is likely
to be lifted next week.
</P>
<P>
Hogg made the statement after a three-hour meeting with EU
Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler in Brussels, according to
a BBC television report.
</P>
<P>
"The EU Council of Ministers is likely to move to support a
relaxation of the ban because of the steps we have taken," Hogg
said.
</P>
<P>
Hogg stressed that the British government would "need to devise
a water-tight system." He also expressed the conviction that the
new system would be acceptable to people who had examined it.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Fischler insisted that measures must be enforced. He
added that controls had to convince people that the prerequisite
for lifting the ban could well be in place.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Fischler, Hogg reportedly put forward a
highly selective slaughter of cattle in exchange for an early
lifting of the ban on British beef.
</P>
<P>
Under the British proposal, some 40,000 cows aged three to six
years which are most at risk from developing BSE or the mad cow
disease will be slaughtered, cutting the number of cases of BSE
this year and next by up to 40 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
