<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechen Government Checks Out Reports about Dudayev's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The pro-Moscow Chechen government
said today that it is checking out facts relating to the reports
about the death of Chechen separatist leader Dzhokhar Dudayev,
according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Sherip Mamadkhadzhiyev, deputy prime minister of the Chechen
government, told Itar-Tass through telephone, "Today we will be
conducting checks of the statement using both official channels
and through civilians."
</P>
<P>
"It is hardly likely that anything will be made certain before
tomorrow morning," he noted.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, Kremlin officials stressed the need to check out the
real fact.
</P>
<P>
The duty officer at the headquarters of the Russian forces in
Chechnya told Itar-Tass that he had no confirmed information about
Dudayev's death as a result of a missile strike near the village
of Gekhi Chu, 30 kilometers southwest of the Chechen capital of
Grozny.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Gekhi Chu was rocketed late on April 21 or early
on April 22, the duty officer said he was not in a position to
give an immediate answer.
</P>
<P>
The news of Dudayev's death came from a statement of Dudayev's
"government of Ichkeri" delivered to the Itar-Tass office in
Grozny by Khozh-Akhmed Yarikhanov, the former leader of the
Dudayev delegation to the 1995 negotiations with Moscow which went
bust after a number of acts of terror staged by pro-Dudayev
militants.
</P>
<P>
Yarikhanov said the dead body was kept near the village of
Gekhi Chu and several men from among Dudayev's closest entourage,
including his aide Dukvakha Ibragimov, had died together with the
Chechen separatist leader.
</P>
<P>
The "government of Ichkeria" announced three days of mourning
for Dudayev, noting in its statement that "26 April 1996 will be a
day for religious arrangements on the occasion of the tragic death
of President of the Chechen Republic of Ichkeria Dzhokhar
Dudayev."
</P>
<P>
Dudayev, 51, a former Soviet general who had made a name for
himself during the Afghanistan war, led the Chechen separatist
movement to break away from Russia. For the past 16 months, he
directed the armed resistance to the Russian forces which entered
Chechnya at the end of 1994 to protect Russia's territorial
integrity against Chechen separatists.
</P>
<P>
According to Itar-Tass, Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who is
now in Khabarovsk in Russia's Far East on his way to China for a
three-day official visit, was informed without delay about media
reports about Dudayev's death.
</P>
<P>
The news agency cited sources close to the Russian president as
noting that the reports about Dudayev's death "need additional
verification and there is no sense in commenting on them until
they are either confirmed or rejected." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
