<HEADLINE> Greece Rejects Turkey's Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government today
rejected Turkey's protest Monday over an incident in the Aegean,
describing it as "a display of bad faith."
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Nikos Athanassakis said that Turkey's
claims were "totally inaccurate."
</P>
<P>
A Greek coastguard vessel fired warning shots early Monday to
stop a Turkish speedboat which had allegedly landed eight illegal
Iranian immigrants on the island near the island of Kastellorizo
in the southeastern Aegean.
</P>
<P>
Coastguard officers arrested the illegal immigrants -- three
men, two women and three children, who are being held on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Ankara said that the speedboat was a fishing vessel inside
Turkish waters at the time of the incident and "was followed
inside Turkish territorial waters and harassed."
</P>
<P>
It also claimed that the boat was shot at 10-15 times resulting
in the injury of a fisherman.
</P>
<P>
Athanassakis said that Greece had rejected Turkey's protest. He
added that in the period 1992-1995 alone, a total of 22,906
illegal immigrants had entered Greece from Turkey, of whom 4,361
had entered the country from the islands and sea regions.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that there was a problem of illegal
immigrants and Turkey refused to enter into a dialogue on the
issue. 
</P>
