<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe International Trade Fair Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe International Trade
Fair (ZITF), the country's premier annual trade event, opened
today in Bulawayo, with the participation of 31 nations.
</P>
<P>
The six-day fair will have the first three days as strictly
traders' days before opening to the public on Friday, with the
highlight being the official opening by President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,500 local and foreign exhibitors were still working on
their stands on Tuesday morning. Among the goods and services
being exhibited are industrial products, household goods,
furniture, motor vehicles, agricultural implements, foodstuffs
and hardware.
</P>
<P>
Business deals totalling some 55.6 million U.S.Dollars were
expected to be concluded at the trade fair.
</P>
<P>
This year's theme, ''Access Africa Through Zimbabwse's Open
Invitation To World Trade'', was designed to enhance Zimbabwe's
economic performance since the country embarked on economnic
reforms more than five years ago.
</P>
<P>
A new feature at the fair would be the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (comesa) group exhibition which was
expected to compensate for the aborted first COMESA fair due to
financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Countries participating in the COMESA group exhibition include
Kenya, Lesotho, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, Swaziland, Zambia
and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
ZITF has also invited buyers from selected African countries
interested in forging trade links with this southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, which is participating for the second time since
the end of apartheid in 1994, is also expecting to enhance trade
relations with countries in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
