<HEADLINE> Seven African Countries To Get Rid Of IDDS By </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and six other African
countries could be rid of Iodine Deficiency Diseases (IDDS) by
the year 2000, a health expert said at a conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Director of the International Council for the
Control of Iodine Deficiency Disorders (ICCIDD ), Francois
Delange, made the statement in accordance with the results of the
studies carried out recently.
</P>
<P>
The other countries where studies were carried out were Kenya,
Cameroon, Nigeria, Tanzania, Zaire and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
In a keynote address to the conference on the ''Sustainable
Elimination of Iodine Deficiency Disorders In Africa By The Year
2000'', Delange said sufficient intakes of iodine could ensure
the elimination of IDDS.
</P>
<P>
Iodine is a nutrient needed by the body in small quantities
for human development, and if deficient, the victims suffers
various diseases including goitres and cretinism.
</P>
<P>
Iodine intake can, however, be boosted by taking iodized salt.
</P>
<P>
Delange said, ''The World Health Organisation, United Nations
Children's Fund and ICCIDD undertook a multi-centre study on the
impact of salt iodization on iodine nutrition in seven African
countries, having theoretically in common that they were supplied
with the same source of iodized salt as Zimbabwe.''
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference, which started on Monday, seeks to
map out strategies for the elimination of IDDS in Africa by the
year 2000. About 181 million people are said to be at risk of
IDDS in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The conference is being attended by about 200 people from 47
African countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
