<HEADLINE> Least Developed Countries Show Modest Growth, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 23 (Xinhua)-- The economies of Least Developed
Countries (LDCS) in the world displayed ''modest progress'' in the
past two years after several years of stagnation, with estimated real
Gross Domestic Product averaging three percent, the annual report of
a United Nations Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) said in a
press statement in the Namibia's capital Windhoek that least
developed countries' 1996 report showed there had been marked
improvement in the economic growth of the world LDCS, reported the
South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNCTAD statement, the African LDCS were estimated
to have attained an average growth of 2.2 percent in 1995, while
Asian LDCS recorded estimated growth of 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The acceleration of growth in African LDCS was largely attributed
to improved commodity prices, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It said that opportunities and risks facing LDCS around the world
were to be discussed at UNCTAD's ninth ministerial session, scheduled
to be held in Midrand near Johannesburg from April 27 to May 11.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N.report, 33 of the world's 48 least developed
countries are in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
