<HEADLINE> Official: Turkish-Israeli Military Agreement Not </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Undersecretary
Anwar Ayman said here today that the recently concluded military
cooperation agreement between Turkey and Israel is not directed
against the interests of any Arab or neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa, the Turkish official said that the widely reported
agreement is not aimed to forge a strategic alliance between
Turkey and Israel.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Turkey has merely normalized its relations
with Israel as several Arab states have already done.
</P>
<P>
Ayman, currently on a visit to Egypt, said that Turkey and
Israel signed the agreement on military training against the
background of normalized relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has reached similar agreements with 16 other countries,
including Egypt and some other Arab states, he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on reports that under its military agreement
with Israel, Turkey might call on the Jewish state to help it
launch air raids against Kurdish rebels in northern Iraq, Ayman
said the reports were erroneous and unfounded.
</P>
<P>
"We are not in need of cooperation with Israel to combat
terrorism in the region, be it in Iraqi territories or elsewhere,
as this is not the objective of cooperation with Israel," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the current situation in Lebanon, the Turkish official said
that Turkey hopes Israeli military offensives against Lebanese
civilians will end immediately so that the Middle East peace
process can be maintained. 
</P>
