<HEADLINE> Cyprus Go All-out to Enter European Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides
said here today the government paid special attention to the
industrial sector in order to create necessary conditions for "new
prospects in the European market."
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the annual general meeting of
the Cyprus Industrialists and Employers Federation, the president
described the Cyprus economy as "satisfactory," saying that the
growth rate in 1995 was around 5 percent, which almost doubles
that of the EU member states.
</P>
<P>
Inflation went down by 2.6 percent satisfying Maastricht
criteria for the first time, Clerides said, noting that the public
deficit is estimated at 1.3 percent of the Gross National Product
(GNP_, compared to an average of 4.7 percent in the EU member
states.
</P>
<P>
"In 1995, Cyprus managed to satisfy all Maastricht criteria, a
target only met by Luxembourg and to a certain extent Ireland and
Germany of all European Union members," the president said.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted the need of focusing more efforts "on
managing long-standing problems faced by the economy such as the
low level of technology and productivity and the high production
costs, which lead to the undermining of the competitiveness of
Cypriot products, especially in the field of manufacturing".
</P>
