<HEADLINE> Cyprus Wants to Amend Military Agreement with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus said today that it wants
to amend the military agreement with Britain under which British
military aircraft are allowed to use airports of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, government spokesman
Yiannakis Cassoulides said that the Cyprus government wants to
amend the agreement and let the Britons use only the airport of
the southern town of Larnaca because of the military works
currently underway near Paphos airport, on the island's western
coast.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the agreement with the British bases on the
island was reached in 1985. Until 1987, the agreement provided for
 the use of Larnaca International Airport by British military
aircraft. Since 1987, they have been using Paphos International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
The agreement gives the British bases the right to use the
Cypriot airports for training purposes and for alternative
landings in cases of emergency.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added this agreement is quite different from the
case of the Israeli aircraft which were granted permission on two
occasions in 1995 to use Cyprus' sovereign air space and conduct
mock touch-downs and take-offs from Paphos airport.
</P>
<P>
He revealed Monday that the Cyprus authorities rejected on
three occasions "an Israeli request to use Paphos airport for the
same purpose in 1996 because of infrastructure work in close
proximity to the airport for the construction of a military base."
</P>
<P>
Britain, the former colonial power in Cyprus, has retained two
sovereign military bases on the island's southern coast, as well
as other facilities, under the 1960 treaty of establishment of the
Cyprus Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
