<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yandarbiyev Succeeds Dudayev as Rebel Chechen Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev, one of the
rebel Chechen leaders, has succeeded the late Chechen separatist
leader Dzhokhar Dudayev in his post as the head of the Chechen
Republic of Ichkeria, the Itar-Tass news agency reported tonight.
</P>
<P>
Khozh-Akhmend Yarikhanov, who led Dudayev's delegation to the
1995 negotiations with Moscow, said that the decision on the
succession was made by the separatist Military Council Monday, "in
keeping with the Constitution of Ichkeria."
</P>
<P>
Yandarbiyev had been vice-president of the Chechen Republic of
Ichkeria.
</P>
<P>
Yarikhanov said that Dudayev died as a result of a missile
attack launched by Russian forces against the area near the
village of Gekhi Chu late Sunday. he said he had seen "Dudayev's
dead body with his own eyes."
</P>
<P>
According to him, Dudayev arrived at the village located 35
kilometers southwest of the Chechen capital of Grozny together
with his wife Alevtina and put up with his bodyguards in the house
of prosecutor Magomed Djzniyev.
</P>
<P>
A satellite communication session was scheduled for Sunday
evening with the person who was to discuss terms of negotiations
on the Chechen settlement proposed by Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Dudayev and his aide Dukvakha Ibragimov left the house where
his wife remained and moved out into the nearby field. The missile
strike which proved fatal for Dudayev hit the area at that moment.
Dudayev was seriously wounded and died on the same day, Yarikhanov
said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on Dudayev's death, the government of Ichkeria
described his death as "another terrorist act" and declared that
the strike had come "at a time when Dudayev was discussing with an
intermediatory by telephone conditions for the negotiations
proposed by Moscow."
</P>
<P>
Rejecting Russian President Boris Yeltsin's peace plan for
Chechnya announced on March 31 as a peace of "cynical
demagoguery," it declared, "We are calling on the people of
Chechnya to rally together in the struggle to defend the
fatherland."
</P>
<P>
The government of Ichkeria proclaimed a three-day mourning for
Dudayev starting Wednesday. The funeral will take place in the
village of Shalazhi, five kilometers southwest of Gekhi Chu.
</P>
<P>
An indirect confirmation of Dudayev's death came from the
leader of the public and political movement Daimokhk, Shamil Beno,
who told Itar-Tass that the situation in the separatist camp "can
become uncontrollable unless the opposition (separatist) forces
make up their minds quick on the division of power."
</P>
<P>
If Yandarbiyev and the most influential among the field
commanders, Aslan Maskhadov, reach an accord promptly, they will
be able to prevent the armed formations from breaking up into
small groups, Beno said.
</P>
<P>
Dudayev, 51, has led the Chechen separatist movement since the
break-up of the Soviet Union. In the past 16 months, he led armed
resistance to the Russian forces in the local republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
