<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana Leader Desires No Economic Dependence On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Regional economic
dependence on South Africa is both undersirable and
unsustainable, visiting Botswana President Ketumile Masire said
today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a special sitting of South Africa's constitutional
assembly, Masire, who is Chairman of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC), said SADC's ultimate goal is to
replace such dependence with a healthier relationship of
inter-dependence and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Masire arrived in South Africa earlier in the day for a
three-day visit to the country at the invitation of President
Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Masire said SADC had developed a concrete
programme of action which would continue to guide cooperation in
various economic, social and political sectors.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral cooperation, Masire said Botswana is looking
forward to a renegotiated southern African customs union
agreement.
</P>
<P>
"The one-sided 1969 agreement must be replaced by a balanced
regime, consistent with the ideals of the present. Subordinating
sovereign states and trading partners to the whims of one country
is no longer sustainable," said Masire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
