<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Anti-China Resolution Foiled Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A draft resolution against China
on human rights sponsored by the European Union and supported by
the United States was vetoed at the 52nd session of the UN
Commission on Human Rights here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of a no-action motion tabled by China in blocking
a vote on the West-sponsored anti-China resolution once again
demonstrates that the practice of power politics by the West in
interfering in other countries' internal affairs by making use of
the human rights issue has become increasingly unpopular and
encountered mounting opposition from developing countries.
</P>
<P>
It was the sixth such failure of the West since 1990, following
increasing discontent among developing countries with the political
confrontation in the Commission created by the United States
and other Western nations.
</P>
<P>
After the end of the Cold War in 1990, developed nations have
obviously replaced the confrontation between East and West with
one between South and North in the Human Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Commission has passed 58 country resolutions since 1992,
almost all of them against developing countries.
</P>
<P>
At the current session, more than 60 developing countries, 10
more than last year, have been attacked by the West during
discussions of human rights records in individual states.
</P>
<P>
The United States vowed to continue to hang the sword of
Damocles over the heads of these governments -- in a deliberate
move to intensify confrontation in the Commission.
</P>
<P>
Some Western nations have long appointed themselves to the role
of human rights "models" and "judges", examining human rights only
in the developing countries, without questioning their own records.
</P>
<P>
The double standards reveal the true purpose of these Western
countries, which is not to truly promote human rights worldwide,
but to engage in power politics and to interfere in other
countries' internal affairs under the human rights banner.
</P>
<P>
More and more representatives from developing countries
pointed out the fact that no country can claim to have
unimpeachable human rights records.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the improvement of the human rights situation
in a country is closely linked with its economic, social and
cultural development. It is also a country's internal affair
which needs no lecturing from others.
</P>
<P>
No country, no matter how rich or how highly developed its
economy, can justify imposing its own values, concept of human
rights, development model or social system upon others, they added.
</P>
<P>
They said that discussion and promotion of human rights should
be undertaken in line with the principles of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights and on the basis of equality and
mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of Tuesday's vote, contrary to the expectations of
the U.S. and certain other Western countries, is evidence that
power politics, confrontation and the imposition of Western values
upon others are doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
The West, in the draft resolution, are forced to recognize the
achievements China has made in its economic reform and development
and in the reform of its legal system in an attempt to gain more
support for their resolution. However they tried again to
discredit China with unwarranted charges.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Western move, devised to damage China's image, was
made more for political purposes than for the genuine promotion of
human rights.
</P>
<P>
It also serves their attempt to contain China, a major power in
the developing world and one of the world's most rapidly growing
economies.
</P>
<P>
China has made clear that it will by no means allow itself to
be pressured into accepting others' values or giving up its own
choice of social system and development model.
</P>
<P>
After repeated failures, the Western countries should see the
need to stop practicing confrontation and double standards over
human rights issues, which is being increasingly challenged by
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Obviously, it is high time for them to change course. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
