<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attempt to Interfere in China's Internal Affairs Foiled: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 23 (Xinhua) -- China said today the failure of
the West to pass an anti-China resolution on human rights shows
that it is against the popular will to use human rights to
interfere in other countries' internal affairs and pursue
hegemonism and power politics.
</P>
<P>
Such act of the West is bound to be opposed by the majority
members of the Human Rights Commission, said a Chinese Foreign
Ministry spokesman while commenting on the adoption of a decision
at the 52nd session of the UN Commission of Human Rights not to
review and vote on the West-sponsored anti-China draft resolution.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the Chinese government's willingness to make
concerted efforts, under the guidance of the principles of the
U.N. Charter, with other members of the international community to
further promote and protect human rights on the basis of equality
and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said "the Chinese government has all along
attached importance to human rights and made tireless efforts and
achieved world-renowned success in promoting and protecting the
human rights of the Chinese people in accordance with the purposes
of the UN Charter and the spirit of relevant international
instruments on human rights and in line with China's specific
conditions."
</P>
<P>
While promoting and protecting the rights to subsistence and
development of the Chinese people, the Chinese government has
persevered in improving democracy and the legal system, he said,
adding that as a result, legal protection of citizen's rights in
the political, economic, cultural and social fields has been
markedly strengthened.
</P>
<P>
While China currently enjoys economic growth, political
stability, national unity and social progress, said the spokesman,
the Chinese people are exercising their human rights in an
increasingly fuller scope.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, some Western countries choose to ignore these
facts and raised once again the anti-China proposal at the current
session through politicizing the human rights issue and adopting
double standard in an attempt to put pressure on China by
exploiting the human rights issue so as to force the Chinese
people to alter the road they have chosen by themselves," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
