<HEADLINE> Nigeria Again Protests Suspension From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has again protested its
suspension from the Commonwealth, the News Agency of Nigeria
reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a letter, dated April 21, to the Secretary-general of the
Commonwealth Chief Emeka Anyaoku, Nigeria's Foreign Minister
Chief Tom Ikimi said that lifting the suspension was necessary so
that the obstacle to dialogue between Nigeria and the
organization could be removed.
</P>
<P>
"However, the impression given to date is one of unfairness
and haste in treating a matter so vital to our country's national
interest and relations with the Commonwealth," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria urges the leadership of the Commonwealth to "treat
urgently and seriously the fundamental issues raised in our
several petitions on this matter," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria was suspended from the Commonwealth during the
organization's meeting in Auckland last year in protest against
the execution of Ken Saro-wiwa and eight other Ogoni men.
</P>
<P>
The letter was written on the eve of a meeting of the
eight-member special Commonwealth ministerial committee to decide
on whether or not further sanctions would be imposed on Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The committee, headed by the Zimbabwean Foreign Minister, Dr.
Stan Madenge, was set up shortly after the suspension to
investigate alleged gross human rights violations and monitor the
nigerian government's commitment to democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The committee has asked for a visit to Nigeria but has been
rebuffed by the Nigerian government. 
</P>
