<HEADLINE> Persson: Sweden Will Not Join NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Sweden has no plans to join the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) and will not be
responsible for the security of its Baltic neighbors, Swedish
Prime Minister Goran Persson was quoted as saying in a local
newspaper today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Helsinky Sanomat on the eve of his
visit to Finland, Persson said that the time was not right for
Sweden to join the military alliance.
</P>
<P>
He said that due to its geographic location, Sweden has adopted
a policy of nonalignment and military neutrality, which are the
best guarantees of the country's interests, long-term security and
the stability of the Scandinavian peninsula as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Persson said that the Baltic countries have the right to choose
their own defense policies and Sweden will not be responsible for
their security.
</P>
<P>
Sweden fully supports the accession by other Baltic nations to
the European Union and respects their efforts to gain NATO
membership, he added.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister begins his working visit to Finland on
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
