<HEADLINE> OAS Demands Respect for Paraguay's Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of American
States has expressed its "full and resolute" support for
Paraguay's President Juan Carlos Wasmosy in his confrontation with
the country's rebellious army commander.
</P>
<P>
The OAS Permanent Council called a special session Tuesday amid
reports that army commander General Lino Oviedo defied a
presidential order to step down from office. The standoff
generated fear of a military coup against the government.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted at the council meeting, the OAS called
for a meeting of the Western Hemisphere's foreign ministers at a
date and place to be determined according to the developments in
Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, while urging the
OAS to "speak up forthrightly and take action" in support of the
Paraguayan government, informed the organization that Washington
had suspended all military assistance to the South American
country effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Clinton administration was prepared to move
promptly in concert with other OAS members to impose economic
sanctions should an "extraconstitutional" regime take power in
Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
"Such an interruption would also lead us to end all bilateral
economic cooperation and work to ensure any undemocratic regime
would be isolated internationally," he warned.
</P>
<P>
A White House spokesman said that President Clinton in a
telephone call Tuesday reiterated U.S. support for Paraguayan
President Carlos Wasmosy's efforts to maintain constitutional rule
in the country.
</P>
<P>
There were unconfirmed reports late Tuesday evening that
General Lino Oviedo had abandoned his rebellion against Wasmosy by
accepting retirement from the armed forces to become the country's
defense minister. 
</P>
