<HEADLINE> U.S. Prepared Against Terrorism During Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. federal authorities
are stepping up activities to get prepared against possible
terrorist attacks during the summer Olympic Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
The 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center in New York and last
year's bombing of the Oklahoma City federal building have provoked
heightened concern about the possibility of some kind of terrorist
attack at the Olympics, The Washington Post said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The terrorist use of poison gas in the Tokyo subway system last
year has sown unprecedented anxiety about threats from
unconventional weapons, it added.
</P>
<P>
During the 17-day event, the Atlanta city's population will be
doubled and about 40 heads of state are expected to come that
requires security protection.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, a task force under Vice President Al Core has been
set up to deal with possible terrorist attack. And a large
security force are being formed for the Games.
</P>
<P>
The force, more than doubling the 12,000 law enforcement
officers that protected the 1984 Olympics in Los Angles, will
consists of 3,000 Army troops, 6,300 National Guardsmen, and
10,000 other police and private security guards, with an
additional force of agents from the FBI and the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms, the Post revealed.
</P>
<P>
In preparing for the worst, the FBI and other agencies are
holding secret exercises against terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a three-day exercise were held in Atlanta against
terrorist nerve gas attack in the city and a plane hijacking at
the Atlanta airport.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Defense Nuclear Agency organized an exercise to
test its ability of dealing with a terrorist detonation of a
nuclear device near the city's center and another drill was
planned to deal with a germ-weapon attack.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the federal authorities will establish two
"explosive centers", where conventional bombs can be detonated or
defused.
</P>
<P>
The cost of these efforts has not been calculated, but the
Pentagon budget for supporting the Games is at least 47 million
dollars and an additional 25 million dollars has been committed
by the Georgia State on security, the paper noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
