<HEADLINE> Cyprus Gives Tacit Approval to Appointment of New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government has
decided not to give a negative reply to the appointment of
U.N. Secretary-General's new envoy for Cyprus, but will give its
tacit approval.
</P>
<P>
This was stated today by government spokesman Yiannakis
Cassoulides after a cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
He told the press that "we will accept the appointment under
protest. A negative reply would create a fresh negative reply
from Turkey and this would mean a vacant post."
</P>
<P>
Press reports said that U.N. Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali contacted President Glafcos Clerides last week to
propose appointment of South Korean diplomat Han Sung Joo as new
U.N. envoy for Cyprus to replace Canada's former Prime Minister
Joe Clark.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was accepted by Turkey, which has rejected the
appointment of an European to the post, namely Portugal's former
Foreign Minister Jose Manuel Durao Barroso.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government had indicated it would favor the
appointment of an European to the post.
</P>
<P>
Cassoulides said the government does not intend to reply to
the U.N. Secretary-General on the appointment of South Korean
diplomat Han Sung Joo.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "we have absolutely no problem with the
person appointed. Neither his country of origin nor the continent
he originates from cause any problem."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, however, pointed out that it considers the
Turkish position on the appointment of a U.N. Cyprus envoy
"unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Han Sung Joo, 55, foreign minister of Republic of Korea in
1993-94, is currently professor of political science and
President of the Ilmin International Relations Institute at Korea
University.
</P>
<P>
The new envoy is expected to succeed Joe Clark, who had failed
to bring the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides closer to a
settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
