<HEADLINE> Fire Delays New York Subway Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The aging subway of New York ran
into chaos again Tuesday night when its southern section was put
under a small fire sparked by short-circuited electrical wires.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 trains carrying about 40,000 commuters were
affected at the busy intersection in Brooklyn, it was reported
here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The short circuit blew three manholes into the air and started
a small fire. Much of the subway service between the boroughs of
Brooklyn and urban center of Manhattan was closed after the fire,
but it was restored by this morning's rush hour, local authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
Three people suffered minor injuries in the fire and nine
trains had to be evacuated, city officials said. About 2,000
people were on each train.
</P>
<P>
Police said that after the manhole covers blew, someone called
from a pay phone to "claim credit" for the explosion. The caller
claimed there were other devices. A police bomb squad was
dispatched but found no evidence of any explosive device. They
said the fire actually started after a short circuit in wires that
may have been worn by corrosion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
