<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Unveils Firearms Amnesty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- British Home Secretary Michael
Howard granted a month-long national firearms amnesty today after
the mass killing in a primary school in Dunblane, central
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Britain was alarmed on March 13 when a gunman armed with four
semi-automatic pistols burst in the school gym and opened fire at
29 children aged four to six. Sixteen pupils and one woman teacher
were killed and another 12 children wounded. Police estimated that
more than 2 million guns are held illegally.
</P>
<P>
Howard announced that the amnesty will last from June 3 to June
30 throughout England, Scotland and Wales, and the amnesty will
allow for illegally-held guns to be handed in to the police
without fear of prosecution, provided they have not been used in
crime.
</P>
<P>
And the amnesty also applied to ammunitions and grenades.
</P>
<P>
The British government has issued about 800,000 firearms
certificates, which must be renewed annually, but police estimated
that there are about 3 million guns in circulation across the
country.
</P>
<P>
The home secretary urged people to search their houses for any
old and unwanted guns and hand them in to the police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
