<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Protection for More Tibetan Cultural Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA April 24 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-six cultural relics in Tibet
have been placed on the protection list by the local government,
bringing the number of protected relics to 67.
</P>
<P>
Sheizhu Namgyai, director of the regional government's culture
department, made the announcement today in Lhasa, capital of the
Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The 56 relics include two grotto temples, 30 ancient or
historical buildings, 13 carved stones, five ancient remains, and
five ancient tombs in the autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
The number of cultural relics in Tibet is 1,721, and includes
13 on the central government's protection list.
</P>
<P>
Namgyai said that Tibet is going to develop a number of
measures to protect cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Tibet will continue assessment, classification, and approval of
other cultural relics in the region, the director said, and relics
will be divided into regional, city, and county categories so that
as many cultural relics as possible will be protected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
