<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Foreign Trade Increases by 14.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's foreign trade
increased by 14.5 percent in 1995 over the previous year,
according to a government annual statistics report available here
today.
</P>
<P>
The report issued by the Planning Ministry Tuesday said that
non-oil trade volume for the oil-rich emirate in 1995 reached 2.5
billion Kuwaiti dinars (8.25 billion U.S. dollars) from 2.2
billion Kuwaiti dinars (7.26 billion dollars) in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
It said the Kuwaiti imports in 1995 rose from 1.9 billion
Kuwaiti dinars (7.26 billion dollars) to 2.3 billion Kuwaiti
dinars (7.59 billion dollars), while the non-oil exports dropped
from 230 million Kuwaiti dinars (759 million dollars) to 217
million Kuwaiti dinars (716 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was on the top of the list of major Western developed
countries exporting to Kuwait as shown in the report while France
came second with a share of 11 percent and Japan third with 9.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's imports from the Gulf Cooperation Council, GCC, states
were also increased but exports to them were down, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
The report did not give a breakdown of the goods imported by
this country.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, as a small Gulf country importing almost all its
necessities, has steadily increased its imports in recent years
since the Gulf war in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
