<HEADLINE> Dudayev's Death Confirmed: Interfax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A top officer at the Russian
troops' command in Chechnya today confirmed reports about the
death of Chechen separatist leader Dzhokhar Dudayev, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Interfax on Tuesday quoted a number of persons close to the top
Chechen separatist as saying that Dudayev "is alive and working as
usual."
</P>
<P>
In a report today, the news agency cited the top officer at
the Russian troops' command in Chechnya as saying: "After
additional checks run by special forces, including those through
our network of agents, the information on Dudayev's death has been
confirmed."
</P>
<P>
Dudayev was mortally wounded after a Russian rocket attack hit
a separatist meeting near Gekhi-Chu village and soon died
there, the officer said.
</P>
<P>
In Chechnya, a top separatist leader, Shamil Basayev, and other
field commanders loyal to Dudayev have confirmed the death of
Dudayev, according to both Interfax and Itar-Tass.
</P>
<P>
Dudayev, 51, a retired Soviet air force general, was elected
president of Chechnya in 1991. Since then he had led the local
republic in trying to break away from Russia.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Moscow backed opposition forces in the republic,
providing them with tanks and fighters for a coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
The coup attempt failed, and in December 1994 the Kremlin sent
40,000 troops into Chechnya to "restore constitutional order."
</P>
<P>
The 16-month-old war in chechnya has left some 30,000 civilians
dead, according to official estimates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
