<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy Benefitting Foreign Financial Institutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The 127 foreign banks and
financial firms now operating in China saw profits growing 50.5
percent to 140 million US dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Assets jumped 61 percent to 19.14 billion US dollars, and loans
rose 68 percent to 12.74 billion US dollars, according to
statistics released by the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
"The huge market and fast-growing economy in China have
provided various opportunities and great benefits to those foreign
financial institutions," said an official with the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Foreign insurance companies, in particular, have shown
impressive gains.
</P>
<P>
Premiums for insurance other than life insurance in the two
foreign underwriters in Shanghai increased to 64 million yuan, and
life insurance premiums at American International Assurance
Co. Ltd (AIA), an affiliate of the American International Group,
stood at almost 400 million yuan, or 23 percent of Shanghai's
total.
</P>
<P>
"Those financial institutions have grown smoothly not only
because of their management and technology but because of the
flexible regulations and preferential tax policies provided by
China's financial authorities," the official pointed out.
</P>
<P>
China has a 15-percent income tax on foreign financial
institutions, while their Chinese counterparts have to pay from 33
to 55 percent in income tax.
</P>
<P>
"Another reason is that China is hungry for funds, and domestic
interest rates are much higher than international markets, leaving
a greater profit margin for those foreign financial institutions,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Most of them started to show a profit only a year or two after
they began operations in China."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
