<HEADLINE> China's Economy Benefitting Foreign Financial Institutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Foreign insurers have found themselves at a great advantage in
China's young insurance market.
</P>
<P>
"A new insurance company hardly ever makes a profit in less
than eight to ten years after it is established," he said. "AIA,
however, seems likely to turn a profit in five years or less."
</P>
<P>
AIA is the first foreign insurance company to be licensed in
China. It opened in Shanghai three years ago.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to open the financial sector further, since
foreign financial institutions have brought management techniques
and funds, and China has become more deeply involved in the world
economy, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Last year China opened 11 cities to foreign banks. These
included Beijing; Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei
Province; Xi'an, capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province;
and Chengdu, capital of northwest China's Sichuan
Province. Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province,
was opened to foreign insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, foreign bank branches will be allowed to open
sub-branches in economic and technological development zones in
Dalian and Tianjin, two port cities in northeast and north China,
and in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
A few more foreign insurance companies will also be licensed
for China's insurance market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
