<HEADLINE> Iran Cancels Demonstrations in Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced its decision here
today that Iranian pilgrims would not stage political
demonstrations during their pilgrimage to Mecca in a bid not to
clash with Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that the decision on
canceling the political demonstrations against the United States
and Israel during haj rituals in Saudi Arabia was made by Iranian
Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
Iran declared early this month that Iranian pilgrims would
stage demonstrations during haj rituals in Saudi Arabia as "a
divine obligation."
</P>
<P>
However, the demonstrations by Iranians were strongly opposed
by the Saudi Arabian authorities, warning that those pilgrims who
want to stage demonstrations should be responsible for any kind of
consequences.
</P>
<P>
According to IRNA, 78,000 Iranian pilgrims would go to Mecca
and Medina this year.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi government banned all political activities during the
pilgrimage. After the Islamic Revolution in Iran in 1979, Iranian
pilgrims insisted on staging political demonstrations and rallies,
saying that the pilgrimage should be used for political aims.
</P>
<P>
The pilgrimage every year reminds people of the bloody Mecca
incident on July 31, 1987, which led to thousands of deaths and
injuries.
</P>
<P>
Some 320 Iranians were killed in the incident when thousands of
Iranian pilgrims clashed with Saudi police in a political
demonstration near the grand mosque in the holy city of Mecca.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
