<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ESCAP Session Resolves to Fight Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The 52nd annual session of the
United Nations Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the
Pacific (ESCAP) today called for a "holistic approach" to the
problem of poverty, acknowledging that the problem is
inter-connected.
</P>
<P>
In a report adopted today, the session urged that increased
access to social services, health and education should go hand in
hand with income-generating schemes to boost the opportunities of
poor people.
</P>
<P>
The ESCAP calls on its secretariat to formulate a regional
strategy and a program of action on rural poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
The three-day annual ministerial session ended here today after
adopting a report containing a total of 11 resolutions ranging
from enhancing intra-Asia and Asia-Europe land bridges to
promoting human resources development among youth.
</P>
<P>
Participants from 47 ESCAP members and associate members agreed
that action is urgently needed to alleviate the region's growing
poverty problem while promoting sustainable development and making
sure that the environment is protected.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Asian-Pacific ministers spelled out different
ways of achieving such objectives, including regional economic
cooperation, poverty alleviation, environment and sustainable
development, transport and communications.
</P>
<P>
The session also urged increased technical assistance to the
poor countries in the region, especially the least developed,
land-locked and island developing countries. A slowdown of
official development assistance and other factors have made life
very difficult for the 13 least developed countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Most delegations to the session, while expressing support for
the work of ESCAP, urged the oldest intergovernmental body in the
region to continue its reforms, to do more and meet less.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also announced that the next year's session will be
held in Bangkok.  
</P>
</TEXT>
