<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Bid to Save Endangered Crane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YUNNAN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are conducting
a research programme to protect the Grus Nigricollis, one of the
most endangered cranes, from extinction. The birds live in the
southwest China's Qinghai-Tibetan plateau.
</P>
<P>
The migratory bird is listed with the Giant Panda as one of
China's first category protected animals. According to a survey
only 5,000 in total are in existence.
</P>
<P>
To save the precious species, the Nature and Culture
Conservation Center, based in Yunnan province, has launched a
special ecological and education research programme on the
endangered bird.
</P>
<P>
The center, co-sponsored by the (Hong Kong) China Exploration
and Research Society and the Yunnan Institute of Geography, sent
researchers to make on-the-spot investigations about the bird,
finding out the bird's basic living ecological environment.
</P>
<P>
Scientists found that the northern-most breeding place for the
bird is located at about 39 degree north latitude and 3,185 meters
above sea level, and the southern-most living place for the bird
is situated at about 25 degree north latitude and with an
elevation of 3,200 meters.
</P>
<P>
To enhance people's animal protection awareness, they wrote and
distributed publicity material, and organized students to make
on-the-spot investigations on the bird.
</P>
<P>
" We should make the youth conscious of animal protection
before they become poachers," said Zhang Fan, director of the
center.
</P>
<P>
Although the the size of the swamp, the natural habitat of the
rare bird, is decreasing, its number is increasing on an annual
basis.
</P>
<P>
"The bird will not disappear with the swamp, it can live
happily in the same habitat as people, if they enhance their
awareness of wild animal protections," said Zhang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project Promotes Sichuan's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Construction of the Three
Gorges Project, the world's largest water-control scheme, has
brought new opportunities for the development of southwest China's
Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years a number of large enterprises
involved in the chemical, electro-mechanical, building materials,
light and textile industries, have sprung up on the periphery of
the project's reservoir area.
</P>
<P>
Part of the reservoir area is located in Sichuan. Thus far,
other parts of the country have poured more than three billion
yuan (about 360 million US dollars) into this area as part of the
efforts to support the construction of the project.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country has implemented 286 new projects for the
area, donated equipment worth 40 million yuan, given technical
training to 8,800 people and helped resettle 3,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The province has grasped this opportunity to promote its
economy, and has issued favorable policies to create more business
opportunities. Various local governments are wooing large
enterprises in particular.
</P>
<P>
Wanxian City, for example, has given the green light to
enterprises from Shanghai, China's largest industrial city, by
setting up the "Shanghai Industrial Park."
</P>
<P>
Fuling City has allowed nine unprofitable enterprises to be
taken over by the Zhejiang Province-based Jinshan Group and
Fangyuan Group. As a result, a new company with a total investment
of 40 million yuan has been established in the city.
</P>
<P>
The Fuling Cigarette Factory, which lost 12 million yuan
annually in the past, has turned profitable since the Yunnan
Cigarette Factory readjusted its structure of products. The Fuling
factory is now one of the most profitable firms in Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Jinhua, deputy mayor of Wanxian City, said that after
cooperating with three enterprises -- Shanghai's Baimao Group,
Jiangsu's Changzhou Diesel Engine Co. Ltd and Shandong's Huasheng
Group, local enterprises have found "huge" market potential for
their products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
