<HEADLINE> Security Tightened in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 24 (Xinhua)-- Security has been tightened in Sri
Lanka's hill country to meet any Tamil rebel threats during the
ongoing plantation workers' strike, according to reports reaching
here today.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan plantation workers' strike, which commenced Monday,
enters its third day without a settlement in sight.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
(LTTE) fighting for a separate Tamil state in the north-east of
the country are likely to use the strike to launch attacks in
plantation areas.
</P>
<P>
However, stiff instructions have been given to all the police
officials in the plantation areas as to how to deal with any
incidents, the reports stated.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that special conferences for the police have
been held in all the divisions in the hill country and all police
stations are located in the vicinity of plantations. Patrolling is
going on day-and night in the estates to see that everything is
peaceful.
</P>
<P>
Situation report on the plantations are sent to the police
headquarters in Colombo every six hours, said the reports, adding
that however, up to now no incidents have been reported.  
</P>
