<HEADLINE> UN Program Welcomes Chinese Volunteers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese volunteers are welcome to
work with the United Nations and apply their special skills and
knowledge to improving the lives of people of other developing
nations.
</P>
<P>
This message came from Susie Jolly, an official with the
Beijing office of the UNDP, who was interviewed by Xinhua here
today.
</P>
<P>
Jolly said that since 1981, when the UN Volunteers signed an
agreement with the Chinese government, more than 120 Chinese have
volunteered to work in over 20 developing countries in Asia,
Africa and Latin-america.
</P>
<P>
This included areas of traditional Chinese expertise in biogas,
agricultural technology, silk-worm production, irrigation, and
civil engineering. In the last few years, the areas have expanded
to optical instruments, computers, and medicine, she said.
</P>
<P>
"They generally work for one or two years abroad, with the
longest being eight years," said Jolly, adding that many Chinese
volunteers have won praise from governments of countries they've
helped.
</P>
<P>
"In many developing countries, stories of Chinese volunteers
are well-known," she said, "such as stories about the
acupuncturist in Western Samoa, the silk-worm specialist in
Pakistan and the optometrists in Syria."
</P>
<P>
She said that, to be eligible for service with UNV, Chinese
citizens should have a good command of either English or French,
at least a bachelor's degree, and more than two years of work
experience.
</P>
<P>
"However, not everybody who signs up for the project can go,"
she explained, "they have to compete with volunteers from other
countries."
</P>
<P>
"The demand for their specializations also affect their chances
of success."
</P>
<P>
Jolly, who can speak Chinese, said that she herself benefitted
from one year of service as a UN volunteer, and that "it is more
useful than going to university."
</P>
<P>
"It is a good opportunity to learn about the operations of the
United Nations and the national condition of China," she said,
adding that she hopes more Chinese citizens will take part in this
grand cause.
</P>
<P>
She also pointed out that while China has sent its own people
to help other nations, more than 160 volunteers from the U.S.,
Britain, Canada, Australia, Singapore, Myanmar, Mauritius, and
other countries have worked in China over the past 16
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
