<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comet Split Reported by Chinese Astronomers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The first report of a splitting
of the nucleus of the Hyakutake Comet has come from the Purple
Mountain Observatory in Nanjing, in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the observatory and its Qingdao affiliate in
Shandong Province made the announcement, based on observations on
April 6, 11, and 13, that the nucleus of the Hyakutake Comet had
split into five pieces, and the position and shape of the pieces
were changing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen Daohan, an astrophysicist at Purple Mountain,
there are many explanations for comets splitting. In the case of
Hyakutake it is most likely that it was caused by solar influences.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that when the observatory first spotted the
splitting on April 6, the comet was only 0.78 astronomical units
(about 117 million km) from the Sun. The distance will be down to
0.23 astronomical units (about 34.5 million km) when the comet
reaches its perihelion, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
He said that this phenomenon is one which is highly valuable
for science in its study of the evolution of comets.
</P>
<P>
Hyakutake Comet, which is six times brighter than Haley's
Comet, was named after an amateur Japanese astronomer, who
discovered it on January 30 of this year. It reached its perigee,
about 15 million km from the earth, on March 23.
</P>
<P>
Purple Mountain Observatory is a prominent center for planetary
and cometary research, and was the first to spot the returning
comet in March.
</P>
<P>
A total of 23 cases of cometary nuclei splitting have been
reported since the Comet Biela split in 1846.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Plans More Sanctions Against Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is facing further
sanctions imposed by the Commonwealth of Nations which is at odds
with the West African state on democracy and human rights.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Ministerial Action Committee on Nigeria, in
its meeting in London on Tuesday, recommended that member states
freeze foreign assets owned by Nigeria's military leaders and ban
the country from all international sporting contests.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria had been suspended from the 52-member Commonwealth
last November following the military government's execution of
Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight ethnic activists.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth had also imposed limited sanctions on the
West African state ruled by the military, including an arms
embargo and boycott of foreign tours by its military leaders.
</P>
<P>
However, a more severe economic sanction, such as an oil
embargo, was rejected by the Commonwealth committee, set up last
November to report human rights situation in the Africa's largest
producer of crude oil and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Delegates of the committee held that an oil embargo will hurt
ordinary Nigerians more than their military leaders as over 80
percent of Nigeria's foreign exchange income comes from the oil
revenue.
</P>
<P>
"To impose further economic measures, we will also need wider
consultations with the United States and the European Union,"
said a statement issued by the committee which is made up of
Canada, Malaysia, Britain, South Africa, Jamaica, New Zealand,
Ghana and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that the Commonwealth "would not go beyond its
present recommendation."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi on Tuesday
delivered a protest to the Commonwealth Secretary General Emeka
Anyaoku.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that lifting the suspension was necessary so
that obstacles to dialogue between Nigeria and the Commonwealth
could be removed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
