<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Less Surplus Expected In China's 1996 Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade surplus is
expected to be narrowed dramatically this year.
</P>
<P>
Increase in exports may drop drastically as China reduced
export rebate rates again in January this year, following the
first cut in July 1995, according to the 1996 China Financial
Outlook, which was released today by the People's Bank of China,
the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Rising domestic demands and a relaxing of import restrictions,
among other factors, will boost imports, the Outlook said.
</P>
<P>
China is not expected to have such a foreign trade surplus as
in 1995 if exports slow down and imports go up, said the Outlook.
</P>
<P>
China had 16.69 billion US dollars in foreign trade surplus and
73.59 billion US dollars in foreign exchange reserves at the end
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics provided by the customs accord with the central
bank's prediction. Over the first quarter, China's exports dropped
8.7 percent, and import surged 23.2 percent, compared with the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Outlook, however, emphasized that consecutive cuts in
export rebates will not thoroughly reverse the growing momentum in
exports, which has continued over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The state has not overhauled policies encouraging exports, and
to hold on original market shares, foreign trade firms will not
curtail exports, said the Outlook, though the reduction in export
rebate has squeezed their profits, weakening export motives.
</P>
<P>
Under the current foreign trade mechanism, expanding exports
are still a major way for enterprises to develop.
</P>
<P>
"So the growing momentum in China's foreign trade will not be
radically turned around," the Outlook added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
