<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNC Advances Deliberation On National Charter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Council has shifted the discussion on the National Charter from
Thursday to 6 p.m. today, according to a report of JMCC, a
Palestinian press service based in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat is currently presiding over a
meeting of the PLO Executive Committee to prepare for this
evening's session.
</P>
<P>
It is not known if the PNC will elect a new PLO Executive
Committee today as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The current 21st PNC session is dubbed as "Building and
Reconstructing the Homeland." Out of the council's 669 members,
536 were present at Tuesday's session. 530 members are attending
today's session.
</P>
<P>
The charter deliberations might end tonight, or continue
through tomorrow. At the end, the members will have to vote on one
of several ideas. Two-thirds majority is set at 446 members,
according to PNC Speaker Salim Zanoun.
</P>
<P>
There are four schools of thoughts on the matter:
</P>
<P>
First, to vote on canceling the articles that Israel wants
deleted. The PNC will appoint its Legal Committee to look into
alternatives to the original charter. The PNC would also approve
an interim political program that the PLO would implement until
the next session of the PNC. The alternatives to the charter
would be based on the peace accords, especially the letters of
mutual recognition of September 1993.
</P>
<P>
Second, to make any change or cancellation of the National
Charter conditional on Israeli acceptance of the principle of
Palestinian self-determination. The basic premise of this position
is that the Palestinians will not have anything left to
presure Israel with after the charter is changed, so they
should get something in return. When Abdul Shafi, who is the
most vocal proponent of the choice, outlined this idea in last
night's session, Arafat lashed out at him and Abdul Shafi
walked out of the session.
</P>
<P>
Third, to vote on replacing the National Charter with the
1988 PNC Declaration of Independence. The declaration accepted
U.N. Resolution 242, recognized Israel and called for a
two-state solution.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, to vote on refusing to change the charter. This
trend is expected to be voiced by Abdul Rahim Mallouh,
leader of the Popular Front for Liberation of Palestine (PFLP),
but is a very minority position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Grows on Trees for Yellow River Communities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- They are proving that money grows
on trees in a once barren area along China's Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of hectares of barren hills along the
famous river in north China's Shanxi Province has been transformed
into a money-spinning corridor. The greening of the hills has
brought vincible interests for local people.
</P>
<P>
Local residents have planted more than 130,000 ha of trees on
the barren hills along the river, 60 percent of which are cash
trees helping peasants to escape poverty.
</P>
<P>
Lin County in Luliang Prefecture, Shanxi Province, has become
the biggest red date production base in the country. For three
consecutive years, annual output volume of red date in the county
surpassed 50 million kg, contributing 40 percent of the per
capita annual income of residents.
</P>
<P>
Fruit trees in the two townships of Huangtanping and Zaoling,
Xiangning County, have produced over 8.2 million yuan (some one
million U.S.dollars) of net income for the local economy, giving
an extra 376 yuan to the per capita annual income of local people.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
