<HEADLINE> More Clashes Claim 13 Lives In South Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen people died and 33
others were wounded when a fierce fighting broke out in south of
the Somali Capital, Mogadishu, last night between militiamen of
Mohamed Farah Aideed and those of his rival, Osman Hassan Ali
Atto, according to hospital sources.
</P>
<P>
According to eyewitness, the fighting broke out when the
militiamen loyal to Mohamed Aideed had launched an artillery and
mortar attack on positions of Osman Atto's men in Bosnia
vicinity, the area controlled by Osman Atto in South Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
During the first stage of the fighting, the armed men
exchanged anti-aircraft missiles, multiple rocked launchers,
and heavy and small machine guns.
</P>
<P>
The thunder and out-burst of the heavy shelling lit the dark
war torn capital with red flares flying over the roofs of the
residential areas throughout Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to Abdi Hassan Awale Qeybdid, the man in charge of
Osman Atto's militiamen, his forces have destroyed three battle
wagons belonging to General Aideed, however, eyewitness confirmed
only one double barrel anti-aircraft missile launcher being
blazed as a result of improper rocket discharge. In general, no
party has made any territorial gain and the fighting seems to
have subsided this morning even though some sporadic shootings
are heard along the front lines dividing the two sides.
</P>
<P>
At least 120 people are believed to have died and nearly 400
others wounded since the armed confrontation started between
Aideed and Osman Atto last month in the southern port town of
Merca, 100 km south of Mogadishu. The clashes in Merca have
spread to the capital where the two sides are still engaged in
bitter clashes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
