<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Adopts New Policies to Improve Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
has adopted several new policies to consolidate its operational
thrusts in a bid to improve the quality of projects in its
developing member countries.
</P>
<P>
Among them, according to the latest issue of the ADB Review,
the policies on governance, inspection function and involuntary
resettlement are particularly significant.
</P>
<P>
The policy on governance marks an important step toward the
promotion of sound development management.
</P>
<P>
To make good governance operationally relevant, the bank will
emphasize accountability, participation, predictability and
transparency.
</P>
<P>
The inspection function establishes a formal grievance
procedure for the benefit of any community, organization or group,
which deems itself adversely affected by a public sector bank
project.
</P>
<P>
Under the policy on involuntary resettlement, all projects
approved by the bank after January 1, 1996, require an initial
social assessment to identify affected population.
</P>
<P>
Involuntary resettlement should be avoided or minimized and,
where feasible, be conceived and executed as part of the project.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bank also intends to make co-financing a
mainstream activity to catalyze additional private capital for
developing member countries.
</P>
<P>
The bank will assist co-financing in appraising and managing
risks. The guarantine facility will be used to enable developing
countries with limited access to capital markets to attract
long-term debt financing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
