<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Egyptian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Egyptian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Al-Ahram:
</P>
<P>
-- At the beginning of the U.N. General Assembly meeting to
examine the Israeli attacks on Lebanon, Lebanese President Elias
Hrawi blamed the international community for its position toward
the continued Israeli attacks on Lebanon, which have killed more
than 100 Lebanese civilians.
</P>
<P>
-- Iraq has accused the U.N. of changing terms of the proposed
agreement allowing it to sell part of its oil to buy food and
medicine for its people, who are suffering under sanctions imposed
by the U.N. on Iraq following its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Al-Gomhuria:
</P>
<P>
-- Six people were killed Tuesday, including three police
officers, in southern Egypt when hundreds of policemen clashed
with terrorists suspected of killing 18 Greeks in Cairo last
week.
</P>
<P>
Al-Akhbar:
</P>
<P>
-- Turkey Tuesday announced that the Turkish-Israeli
cooperation agreement is not involving a strategic alliance
between the two countries, saying that the agreement is not
directed against the interests of any Arab or any other
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. efforts to halt the conflict between Israel and
Hezbollah in Lebanon made little headway Tuesday as both sides
kept up the rain of rockets and shells.
</P>
<P>
-- Egypt's People's Assembly Speaker Ahmed Faghi Sorour said
Tuesday that the upcoming visit of the Egyptian parliamentary
delegation to Israel was canceled in protest at its 13-day
bombardment of southern Lebanon. 
</P>
