<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Not to Expand Free Trade Area to NZ, Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) will not expand its free trade area to the Common
Economic Region (CER) of New Zealand and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Undersecretary Cesar Bautista said today
that the economic ministers of the ASEAN will discuss the
ASEAN-CER ties when they meet late this week in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We are not yet ready at this point in time," citing
that the ASEAN's hesitancy to forge formal free trade with the CER
at this point is largely due to the wide disparity in both
regions' level of economic development.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the ASEAN is amenable to easing up
customs rules to facilitate trade between the two regions.
</P>
<P>
Among the customs rules that the ASEAN is willing to relax for
the CER is on phytosanitary procedures.
</P>
<P>
He said that the harmonization of the phytosanitary procedures
will be reviewed by the ASEAN Secretariat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
