<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Concerned Over Imports Outpacing Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government today
expressed concern that the growth in imports has outpaced exports
in February, the first time in many months.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Undersecretary Cesar Bautista noted that
although exports are growing but the rate of increase is lower
than the growth in imports.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Statistics Office, total trade in
February increased by 37 percent to 3.951 billion US dollars over
2.876 billion dollars in February last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports went up by 45.9 percent in February to 2.357
billion dollars from 1.616 billion dollars in February 1995.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, exports grew only by 26.5 percent to 1.594
billion dollars from 1.260 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time in many months that the growth in
imports outpaced exports," he indicated.
</P>
<P>
However, he explained that it is just normal for a developing
economy like the Philippines to register increases in imports as
long as the growth would not outpace exports.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the trend could be corrected in
the succeeding months.
</P>
<P>
The government is targeting a 50 billion dollar export level by
the year 2000 to attain a newly industrializing country status
from the 21 billion dollar target this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
