<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Perry, Peres to Discuss Missile Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Perry said Tuesday that he would discuss Israeli anti-missile
defenses with Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres when the latter
comes to Washington this weekend.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a gathering in downtown Washington of the
Anti-Defamation League, a Jewish rights group, Perry said that he
and Peres will discuss theater missile defense and other weapons
systems the two countries are jointly developing to further
bolster Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said that Peres would visit Washington from
Sunday to Tuesday, during which he and Perry would sign a
memorandum on joint missile defense cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"The United States and Israel are jointly developing systems
such as the Arrow anti-tactical missile system and high-energy
lasers that will be able to knock rockets and lasers out of the
air closer to their launcher point than previous systems," Perry
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are also looking at some new initiatives in the area
dealing with early warning. All of these programs we will discuss
very seriously and in a very substantive way with the prime
minister when he is here this weekend," he added.
</P>
<P>
Perry vowed once again that the United States would continue to
ensure Israel's military superiority in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"As long as I am the secretary of defense for the United
States, we will maintain the qualitative edge in Israel."
</P>
<P>
To attain that end, the United States provides Israel with 3
billion dollars a year in foreign aid, 1.8 billion dollars of it
for defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
