<HEADLINE> Dubai Re-Exports Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The value of re-exports in
Dubai in 1995 decreased 22.7 percent from that of 1994, Gulf News
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, citing Dubai Customs Department statistics, said
that Dubai re-exported goods -- mostly in the form of machinery,
electrical equipment and textiles -- worth 883 million
U.S. dollars in 1995, down from 1.143 billion dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the fall to the reduction of Iran's
import from Dubai, since the largest market of Dubai has been
controlling the hard currency for saving in order to service its
estimated foreign debt of some 30 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Iran faces rescheduled annual debt
repayments of some 5 billion dollars, nearly a third of total budgeted
oil export revenues of 15.99 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
