<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dudayev to Be Buried, Succeeded by Yandarbiyev </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Chechen separatist leader Azhokhar
Dudayev, who was reportedly killed in a rocket strike in the
village of Gekhi-Chu on Sunday night, is likely to be buried
today, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It quoted "an informed source" in the Moscow-backed Chechen
government as saying that Dudayev may be buried near the grave of
his mother in the settlement of Salazhi, some 35 kilometers
southwest of the Chechen capital of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
The death of Dudayev was confirmed by well-known Chechen
terrorist leader Shamil Basayev, who declared on rebel television
yesterday that Dudayev's power had been transferred to the
vice-president of the rebel regime Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass cited the independent Chechen news agency as saying
that Basayev at first opposed the transfer of Dudayev's powers to
Yandarbiyev, but later agreed to have the vice-president rule
until the election of a new separatist leader.
</P>
<P>
The news agency said that Basayev and some other field
commanders opposed Yandarbiyev to be Dudayev's successor at a
joint session of the defense council and the government of the
separatists on Monday. However, it was finally decided to
transfer Dudayev's power to Yandarbiyev in accordance with the
existing separatist constitution.
</P>
<P>
The local news agency warned that "the death of Dzhokhar
Dudayev could throw Chechnya into a war of clans if field
commanders had preferred their chief of staff Aslan Maskhadov as
the new leader" instead of the 44-year-old Yandarbiyev, who was
appointed vice-president in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some of Dudayev's supporters challenged the reports
of Dudayev's death. The vice premier of the separatist government,
Khasan Kazuyev, who is based in Istanbul, told the Interfax news
agency that he had talked to Dudayev by satellite telephone on
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said that
even if the death of Dudayev is officially confirmed, the
Kremlin's peace plan for Chechnya "will not change in any way,"
Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was echoing Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who
said in Khabarovsk in Russia's Far East this morning: "With or
without Dudayev we shall wind up everything in Chechnya in
peace. There will be no war."
</P>
<P>
The Russian premier is waiting for an official confirmation of
Dudayev's death, Itar-Tass said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
