<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Nigeria to Strengthen Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Trade Minister Wu
Yi told visiting Nigeria Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi in Beijing
today that China is willing to have closer trade ties with
Nigeria, which has become China's third biggest trade partner in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that China attaches much importance to its trade and
economic cooperation with Nigeria, and Chinese commodities are in
line with the demands of Nigerian markets. But despite this
bilateral trade volume covered only one percent of Nigeria's total
last year.
</P>
<P>
She said that China hopes it will export more to Nigeria while
increasing its imports from the African country, and China hopes
that Nigeria would import more of its farm machinery, complete
sets of equipment, and small-sized power generators.
</P>
<P>
Co-chairing the third session of Sino-Nigerian Joint Committee
on Trade and Economy today, Wu said that China's trade ties with
Nigeria have developed smoothly since the committee's previous
session 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Last year, trade volume between China and Nigeria reached 210
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
It is the foothold of China's foreign policy to strengthen and
develop its friendship and cooperation with developing countries,
Wu said, and China is willing to have closer cooperation with
Nigeria in the fields of agriculture, iron and steel, power,
development of water resources and harbor dredging.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that since the establishment of diplomatic ties in
1971, China and Nigeria have enjoyed a sound relationship, and
they have made great achievements in the cooperation in the fields
of politics, economy and culture.
</P>
<P>
China is the largest developing country and Nigeria is the
country with the biggest population in Africa, Wu said, and China
treasures the long-term and sincere friendship between the peoples
of the two countries, and is willing to promote the friendship on
the basis of equality, mutual benefits and peaceful co-existence.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi said that his large delegation shows the desire of the
Nigerian government to expand its trade ties with China, and he
expects the current session will become a new start for bilateral
trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Both Nigeria and China implement policies of non-interference
in other's internal affairs, Ikimi said, and China's efforts in
supporting and safeguarding the rights and interests of developing
countries has left a great impression on the Nigerian people.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also agreed to encourage businesses to invest
in each other's country and create more favourable climate for
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
