<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Protect Wetland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will carry out a
consultancy study to develop a conservation strategy for a
1,500-ha wetland of international importance in the northwest of
the territory.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture and Fisheries Department today signed a
contract with a consultancy firm, which will be responsible for
the study.
</P>
<P>
According to Dr. Lawrence Lee, director of Agriculture and
Fisheries, the study is to assess possible threats and land-use
impacts on the wetland ecological system and to identify
environmental, social and economic issues related to the
conservation of the site.
</P>
<P>
Aspinwall Clouston Limited will lead a consultancy team to
conduct the nine-month study beginning on May 1 this year. Local
and overseas wetland ecologists, ornithologists, zoologists,
botanists and management specialists will join in the
work. Wetland International will set conservation objectives and
strategy for the program.
</P>
<P>
The reserve area, covering 1,500 hectares in Mai Po and Inner
Deep Bay, was listed as a Wetland of International importance
under the Ramsar Convention in September 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
