<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Cautious On China's Inflation Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Experts from the People's Bank of
China, the central bank, are cautiously optimistic that China's
inflation will stay on a downward track this year.
</P>
<P>
"A sound foundation" has been laid for further curbing of
inflation, they said in the 1996 China Financial Outlook, released
today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
More people from all walks of life have agreed that the
government is giving top priority to curbing inflation in
long-term economic control, and the government has taken
initiatives, instead of being forced, to fight inflation.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has adhered to the moderately tight monetary
policy. If it forces the growth rate of the supply of M2, currency
in circulation plus enterprises' deposits down to 25 percent,
prices will keep going down over the rest of this year.
</P>
<P>
About 9.7 percent of the inflation in 1995 was due to price
hikes in the second half of the previous year, and the percentage
in this year will be reduced to around three percent, providing
large room to regulate prices.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture will remain a main inflation booster.
</P>
<P>
"A lean year and lack in agricultural product supply will push
up prices," warned the experts, and given other expected measures
to regulate prices, "it will be a very arduous job to control
inflation within the schedule range."
</P>
<P>
China plans for its gross national product to expand eight
percent, and the nationwide retail price index to surge ten
percent in 1996. It is making efforts to put the growth rate of
the supply of M2 at 25 percent, that of M1, currency plus all
kinds of deposits, at 18 percent, and that of M0, currency in
circulation, at 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The economic growth rate will possibly be lower than in 1995
as the increase in money supply is expected to slow down," they
pointed out, "But the growth rate will not be much lower than in
1995", because the real increase in money supply will be close to
that in 1995, given the slowing down of inflation and lower prices.
</P>
<P>
The first annual China Financial Outlook was published in 1994,
including two main reports on macro economy and monetary policy,
and dozens of reports on reforms, development and opening-up in
the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The new Outlook released today has a special report
illustrating the reforms, goals, policies and measures to put
these goals into reality, and prospects, environment, challenges
facing the financial sector in the next five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Medical Industry Aiming at World Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- China is aiming to develop more
medicines which are competitive in the world market, said Zheng
Xiaoyu, director of the State Pharmaceutical Administration today.
</P>
<P>
He told a national medical conference in Beijing today that new
medical products are expected to make up a quarter of the total
output of the Chinese medical industry by the year 2000, and 30
percent, in 2010.
</P>
<P>
The development of new medicines should focus on products
protected by intellectual property rights, and those that can be
used to cure or treat both common and complicated diseases, said
Zheng. He added that ten new medicines which will be the first of
their kinds both on the domestic and world markets are expected to
be developed in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
China will promote the introduction of foreign advanced science
and technology to the medical industry, and set up ten medical
enterprises and groups with a sales volume of over five billion
yuan each in next fifteen years, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the export of preparations should be promoted, and
80 percent of the new products should meet world standards by the
year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Zheng said that Chinese medical enterprises should co-operate
with foreign companies which applied for administrative protection
from the Chinese government for their patent medicines, and
introduce more effective medicine and medicines of special use
from foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, more than 40 kinds of foreign patent medicines have
obtained administrative protection from the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
