<HEADLINE> Chechen Rebel Commander Confirms Dudayev's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Chechen rebel commander Shamil
Basayev has confirmed that rebel leader Dzhokhar Dudayev has been
killed in a Russian missile strike, the Interfax news agency said
today.
</P>
<P>
The agency reported from the Chechen capital Grozny that
Basayev announced Dudayev's death on rebel television late
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Basayev said a three-day mourning period would be observed for
Dudayev.
</P>
<P>
He added that the 44-year old Vice President of Dudayev's
regime, Zelimkhan Yandarbiyev, was appointed as rebel leader.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency, quoting Chechen rebel government
sources, reported yesterday that Dudayev was killed in a rocket
attack Sunday night near the settlement of Gekhi Chu, 30
kilometers southwest of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
On the news of Dudayev's death, Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said in an interview with Itar-Tass that "with or without Dudayev,
we will settle everything in Chechnya peacefully all the
same. There will be no war there."
</P>
<P>
The president, in the Far East city of Khabarovsk on his way to
China, condemned Dudayev as an instigator of war.
</P>
<P>
"It was he (Dudayev) who wanted war, while we wanted peace. We
several times offered him to sit down at the negotiating table to
begin talks and end the conflict peacefully, but he did not
agree," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
Both the Moscow-backed Chechen government and the Russian
military have said the fact of Dudayev's death should be checked
out.
</P>
<P>
Dudayev, 52, declared Chechen independence in 1991. He had been
hiding in the mountains since Moscow sent Russian troops to the
Caucasian republic in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
On March 31 Yeltsin announced a halt to large-scale military
operations, a partial withdrawal of troops and an offer of
indirect talks with Dudayev. 
</P>
</TEXT>
