<HEADLINE> Heilongjiang Gateway to Russian Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- One third of China's frontier
trade with the Russian Federation is brought about by China's
northernmost Heilongjiang Province, which borders Russia.
</P>
<P>
The province had more than 7.6 billion US dollars in frontier
trade during the past five years, more than three times the figure
during the previous five years.
</P>
<P>
The 1991-1995 period saw the province score a total of more
than 14.4 billion US dollars in foreign trade, with annual growth
rate reaching 18.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year, local foreign trade surpassed 3.4 billion US
dollars, more than 26 times the 1980 figure, exceeding the target
for the year 2000 ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
The province contracted more than 4,450 foreign-funded
projects, and used 1.71 billion US dollars worth of overseas
investment during the 1991-1995 period.
</P>
<P>
It also used a total of 480 million US dollars-worth of
overseas loans, signed three billion US dollars-plus-worth of
contracts to construct foreign projects, and sent more than 86,000
workers to do jobs abroad.
</P>
<P>
It set up five state-level economic and technological
development zones and 23 province-level zones, and opened 23
ports, 17 of which are already operational. 
</P>
