<HEADLINE> Australian Wage Growth Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The ease of inflationary
pressures in Australia was further confirmed today by figures
showing a slowdown of wage growth in the three months to February
this year.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the Australian Bureau of
Statistics (ABS), full-time adult ordinary time earnings increased
by only 0.4 percent in the February quarter.
</P>
<P>
And the annual wage growth rate in the year to February stood
at 3.7 percent, much lower than the highest safe limit of 4.5
percent annually, set by the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA).
</P>
<P>
Today's wage figures suggested that inflationary pressures have
eased. Statistics released by the ABS yesterday showed that the
inflation rate in the year to March dropped to 4.2 percent from
5.1 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Federal Industrial Relations Minister Peter Reith said the wage
figures were consistent with low inflation.
</P>
<P>
"It's an encouragement, as to where we have been and therefore
where we might go in the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
Former board member of the RBA Bob Gregory said, "If you look
at these numbers alone, they won't trigger an interest rate
increase, that would have to come from overseas or a number that
was bigger than this."
</P>
<P>
He said that the RBA would like to see wage claims even lower
although today's figures indicated inflation would come down
further.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Treasury spokesman Gareth Evans said that although
the inflation rate was back to 4.2 percent before the Labor Party
lost office in the federal election in March, there was still
possibility that wages growth over the next year would exceed five
percent.
</P>
<P>
Lessened inflationary pressures were good news for the
Coalition Government, which is striving to reduce the budget
deficit, local press reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
