<HEADLINE> Active Role for Chinese Farmers in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Yang Wanchun and Xu Shoucai have
become "farmer ambassadors" among Tongjiang's citizens, in the
city in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, and have even
opened offices in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Yang, who is a farmer in Tongjiang, led a group of 80 farmers
to contract to manage six greenhouses and 80 hectares of land for
melons, vegetables, and grain in Nizhneleninskoe City in Russia.
Within half a year, they had earned themselves 4,000 tons of
fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
Xu, on the other hand, took 40 other farmers, and got lumber in
return for a contract for growing vegetables in Bikin City. He
also signed an agreement with the city to sell medical equipment
worth 200,000 yuan (about 24,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Farmers in a dozen counties or cities in the province have
got into agricultural production, construction, timber,
fisheries, and processing.
</P>
<P>
Farmers from the border city of Suifenhe were the first group
of Chinese to grow vegetables in Russia, and since 1990, have
been in the vanguard of Sino-Russian barter trade. They even
produced a 10-kg water melon, and their skill and hard work also
won the local people's admiration.
</P>
<P>
At present, over 60 companies owned by Chinese farmers are
playing an important role in the city's business. Some trading
companies, like Great Wall and Qianjin, have even set up
their businesses in Russia.
</P>
<P>
The city's farmers have cut quite a figure in the international
railway business by transporting tons of goods to and from
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Another border city, Heihe, has been giving preferential
policies for farmers doing business. Business streets, retail
sales markets, farm produce markets, and fairs have been set up
all across the city.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that since 1989, in Heilongjiang alone, more
than 10,000 people have gone to Russia annually to provide labor,
to do business, or to learn technical skills.  
</P>
</TEXT>
