<HEADLINE> Tarnoff: U.S. Troops off Bosnia by Mid-Dec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. official said
today that the Clinton administration wanted the 20,000 U.S.
troops involved in the NATO peace implementation force in Bosnia
to be withdrawn from Bosnia by December 14.
</P>
<P>
"Our policy is to have all U.S. troops out on or about the 14th
of December," Undersecretary of State Peter Tarnoff told the House
International Relations Committee. "There is no plan to delay the
withdrawal," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The date of December 14 marks the expiry of the NATO force's
one-year mandate, as outlined in the Dayton peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Longstreth, the Pentagon's Bosnia Task Force director,
said that the Defense Department plans to "begin the withdrawal to
allow sufficient time to have the mandate completed by the
one-year point."
</P>
<P>
But Pentagon officials indicated that if the Bosnia
peacekeeping mission is extended under NATO leadership, U.S.
troops would be involved. They would likely be based in
neighboring countries to perform tasks such as command and
control, logistics, communications and other support functions.
</P>
</TEXT>
