<HEADLINE> twelve million badies saved from retardation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- World awareness to the effects of
iodine deficiency last year saved the lives of at least 12
million children born to mothers who previously had low levels of
iodine, the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) said in
harare on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Senior advisor on micro-nutrients at UNICEF headquarters in
New York David Alnwick said this development was a result of
efforts made in the universal salt iodisation over the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
''Twelve million children per year have been saved from some
degree of mental retardation,'' Alnwick told an international
conference on the elimination of iodine deficiency disorders
(IDDS) in Harare.
</P>
<P>
Alnwick said UNICEF has data from 83 developing countries
around the world, which showed global progress in salt
iodization, a process which ensures adequate iodine intakes to
prevent diseases such as goitres and cretinism.
</P>
<P>
''At the end of 1995, 34 of these countries were iodising over
75 percent of their salt, and the proportion of salt being
iodised in most of the other countries was rapidly increasing,''
Alnwick said.
</P>
<P>
The conference which seeks to work out strategies for the
elimination of iodine deficiency disorders in the continent by
the year 2000, has attracted about 200 participants from 47
African countries. enditem

