<HEADLINE> Burundi Guerrillas Have No Base In Tanzania, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
has refuted the allegations last week by Burundian authorities
that guerrillas based in Tanzania were using Lake Tanganyika as a
transit to hit targets in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The Director of Information, Research and Policy Planning in
the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Co-operation,
Cyprian Majengo, told reporters here on Tuesday that the claims
were fabricated to undermine current efforts to resolve the
Burundi political crisis.
</P>
<P>
Lask week, the Pan African News Agency (PANA) reported a ban
on fishing in Lake Tanganyika imposed by the Burundian
authorities over the allegations that the lake was being used by
anti-government guerrillas based in Tanzania and Aaire as a
launching pad.
</P>
<P>
According to PANA, the ban was a result of persistent claims
by the army headquarters in Bujumbura that assailants from the
two neighbouring countries were passing through the lake to hit
targets in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Majengo said that always Tanzania had maintained her position
respecting the non-interference in domestic affairs of any
country and disallowing the refugees to use her territory as a
military incursion base against their country of origin.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government will continue respecting the
international law on refugees which among other things, bars a
host country to allow refugees to involve themselves in
activities vis a vis their country of origin, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, retired President Mwalimu Julius Nyerere on Tuesday
held talks in Mwanza with two Burundi political parties, the
ruling Frodebu, a party dominated by the majority Hutus and the
opposition Uprona dominated by manority Tutsis. The talks are
aimed to seek ways to end the political conflicts stimmering in
Burundi since the October 23 1993 failed coup d'etat when Burundi
President Melchior Ndadaye was assassinated by members of the
Burundi armed forces dominated by minority Tutsis.  
</P>
