<HEADLINE> Foreign Companies Form Groups for Three Gorges Bids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen big-name companies
worldwide have formed four groups to compete for the bids which
China will invite in the second quarter of this year for the
purchase of large turbogenerators for the Three Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
According to the Yangtze River Three Gorges Development
Corporation (YRTGDC), the major undertaker of this, the world's
largest water-control project, 14 out of a total of 26
turbogenerators, each with an installed capacity of 700,000 kw,
will be purchased through international bidding.
</P>
<P>
The total investment in the project is estimated at 200 billion
yuan (about 24 billion US dollars). Of the total, more than 100
billion yuan will go into core projects, while funds needed by the
electromechanical and electromechanical-related metal structures
will need one third of this amount.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the turbogenerators have roused great interest among
manufacturers across the world, said a spokesman for the YRTGDC.
</P>
<P>
Energomachexport, the Leningradsky Metallichesky Zavod Joint
Stock Co. and the Electrosila Corporation have formed the Russian
group; the anglo-French GEC Alsthom, ABB of Switzerland and
Kavaerner of Norway have formed Europe's federation; German firms
Voith and Siemens have united with GE of Canada; and Japan's group
consists of Hitachi, Toshiba, Mitsubishi Electric Corporation,
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd, the Ito Corporation and the
Mitsui Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The groups have said that they will bring with them capital to
participate in the bidding. They are negotiating with their
countries' export credit agencies for support, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, a number of well-known commercial banks have
expressed their intention to provide commercial loans matching
credit exports.
</P>
<P>
These banks are said to have realized that the loans involve
few risks because the project is backed by the Chinese government
and is sure to get export credits from other countries.
</P>
<P>
In addition, involvement in the fund-raising activities will
provide commercial banks with opportunities to enter the Three
Gorges market and establish broad commercial links with
manufacturers participating in the bidding, the official
explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
