<HEADLINE> India's Media Urged to Help Low-key Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Concerned over the low-key
campaign in the country, India's Election Commission has decided
to direct the state media to help in voter awareness, the Times of
India reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to Election Commissioner M.S. Gill, the commission
has written to both Doordarshan (state television) and the All
India Radio (air) to at least inform the public of the various
candidates in the fray.
</P>
<P>
The ballot papers can physically be shown on television, two or
three times so as to inform the voters about the candidates in
their constituencies by giving the candidates' names and the
symbols they are contesting under, Gill said.
</P>
<P>
Likewise the air can announce the candidates and their symbols
in serial order, so that the voter has some basic information. At
the same time, the state-owned media could also chip in by urging
the voters with something such as "do come and vote."
</P>
<P>
The low-key campaign is a fallout of election expenditure
ceiling of a maximum of 450,000 rupees (about 12,900 US dollars)
for each seat in Lok Sabha (lower house of parliament) as well as
the Indian Supreme Court's recent ruling which clubs the party's
expenditure to that of its candidate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
