<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Southern Africa Enters New Era Of Peace, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 24 (Xinhua)-- Zimbabwe and Zambia are insisting
on economic reforms and attracting more foreign investment in the
past few years, thus laying a foundation for future economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has made encouraging progress in its efforts to
resuscitate the economy which was ravaged by the protracted civil
war. Its GDP rose by three percent last year while its inflation
rate declined to 51 percent in 1995 from 71 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Angola, another war-torn nation in the region, has finally
started national rehibilitation as the peace process in the
country is moving steadily.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a new trend of regional economic cooperation and
integration has emerged in the region in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The leaders in the region have realized that regional cooperation
and integration are necessary because no single nation can achieve
sustained growth and development in isolation.
</P>
<P>
Against the background of emerging economic blocks in the world,
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) was born out of the
loose Southern African Development Coordination Conference (SADCC) in
1992, marking an important step on the road towards the regional
integration.
</P>
<P>
The SADC Plan of Action consisting of some 400 projects has
been worked out, which needs investment of about 8.5 billion US
Dollars. Scores of projects are being implemented to enhance the
regional cooperation in the fields of agriculture, mining,
transport, industry and human resources development, among
others.
</P>
<P>
A protocol on shared water course systems and a memorandum of
understanding on setting up a regional power pool were signed at
the SADC Summit last August. The two documents have charted
common strategies for the conservation and utilizatin of water in
this drought-prone region and closer coordination in the
developnment of hydro-electric and other power resources.
</P>
<P>
The SADC countries have held successive meetings since the
beginning of this year to map out common strategies for
expanding foreign trade, attracting investment, applying advanced
technologies, and enhancing bilateral and multilateral
cooperation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, a number of draft protocols on regional free
trade, free movement of people as well as cooperation in the
fields of food and agriculture, mining and tourism are in process
of development, according to the SADC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Endowed with rich natural resources, the SADC region has great
potential for economic development and cooperation. Under the new
historial conditions, the region's prospects for economic
development are more brilliant than ever before. enditem


=04240701

=04240701
NNNN
15:01 15:02 g # PAB
