<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Foreign Trade Backed by Interior </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region is relying on China's interior provinces and regions to
boost trade with neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianguo, director of the regional bureau of foreign
economic co-operation and trade, said that more than 40 percent of
Xinjiang's import and export volume originates in other provinces
and regions. The figure reached about 500 million US dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
Until 1990, Xinjiang did not have any trade with the
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
In June 1992 the central government gave approval to Xinjiang's
three border cities of Yining, Tacheng and Bole and this regional
capital to open wider to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang's foreign trade volume reached 1.428 billion US
dollars-worth last year, up from 459 million US dollars-worth in
1991.
</P>
<P>
Its annual trade seminars held here since 1992 have been
attended by about 10,000 overseas business people, and concluded
transactions worth a total of more than 7.5 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Without the trade seminars, Xinjiang's foreign trade could not
have developed so quickly," Wei noted.
</P>
<P>
To extend trade relations with other parts of the country, the
region is building its largest shopping center to display and sell
quality and brandname goods from all corners of the country.
</P>
<P>
Experts here predicted that the co-operation between Xinjiang
and interior parts of the country will surely enliven the trade
relations between Xinjiang and the neighboring countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
