<HEADLINE> Indonesia Sets 13 Integrated Development Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto has
designated 13 integrated development areas in Indonesia's eastern
part (KTI) in an effort to accelerate the region's development, a
senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting of the KTI development board here Tuesday,
Soeharto also decided to let the provinces in the KTI region to
enter into cooperation with other regions and foreign countries,
especially with provinces involved in the "SIJORI" Growth
Triangle, said Research and Technology minister Habibie, according
to the local press today.
</P>
<P>
"SIJORI" stands for Singapore, Johor of Malaysia and Riau of
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The 13 integrated economic development areas located in the
eastern region of Indonesia include East Timor, Maluku, Irian
Jaya, West and East Nusa Tenggara, Kalimantan and Sulawesi.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the western part of Indonesia, including Java and
Sumatra islands, the development of the eastern region has been
slow.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate in the eastern region is only about six percent
while the western region enjoys a growth rate of eight percent,
said the minister.
</P>
<P>
"To fully develop the eastern part, a 10 percent growth rate
must be achieved," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
