<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news in Latin America during the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Petroleum Investments to Increase in Brazil
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Petrobras, Brazil's state-owned petroleum
company, will invest 3 billion U.S. dollars this year in the
exploration and production of the sector.
</P>
<P>
The investments will form part of the authorities' plan to
reach a petroleum production of 1.5 million barrels per day by the
end of this century, said sources close to Petrobras.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Brazil had a daily oil production volume of 820,000
barrels which satisfied half of its domestic consumption.
</P>
<P>
IMF, IDB and WB to Offer Loans to Venezuela
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF), the World
Bank and the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) will grant 3.3
billion dollars worth of loans starting next year to back the
economic adjustment measures announced last week by Venezuelan
President Rafael Caldera.
</P>
<P>
Of those loans, 1.4 million dollars will be contributed by the
IMF, 900 million by the World Bank and one billion by the IDB,
according to Venezuelan Finance Minister Luis Raul Matos Azocar.
</P>
<P>
Mining Ministers of Americas to Hold Meeting
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Seventeen countries have confirmed their attendance
to the first conference of mining ministers of the Americas which
will be held in Santiago, Chile, on May 15-16.
</P>
<P>
The ministers from Mexico, Venezuela, Peru, Ecuador, Bolivia,
Argentina, Canada, Colombia and Chile will be among those
participating in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Mexico Reports 1.673 Billion Dollars Surplus in First Quarter
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico reported a 1.673 billion dollars trade
surplus in the first quarter of this year, said the Finance
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The surplus was the result of 21.980 billion dollars worth of
exports and 20.307 billion dollars worth of imports. Overseas
sales increased 17 percent while imports increased 11.6
percent over the same period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Colombia's Current Account Deficit Climbs to 741.7 Million Dollars
</P>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA -- Colombia's current account deficit for the
January-March 15 period totaled 741.7 million dollar, an increase
of 42.7 percent over the same period in 1995, said the Banco de la
Republica.
</P>
<P>
The climbing deficit was the result of the fact that payments
abroad for imports and services exceeded the exports and sales of
services over the period.
</P>
<P>
Brazil to Import 2.638 Million Dollars Agricultural Products
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil will import this year more than 8
million tons of farm products worth a total of 2.638 billion
dollars due to a decrease in local production.
</P>
<P>
Of the imports, 5.7 million tons will be wheat, 1.5 million
tons will be corn, 680,000 tons rice, and 360,000 tons cotton.
</P>
<P>
According to forecasts, Brazil's agricultural output will drop
13 percent in 1996 compared with that of last year,
</P>
<P>
Argentine Wool Exports Drop 16.3 Percent
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Exports of Argentine wool totalled 14.2 million
dollars in February, a reduction of 16.3 percent with respect to
the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the wool exports reached a total volume of 6,228
tons, an increase of 18.64 percent.
</P>
<P>
Overseas sales of wool made between July 1, 1995 and February
29, 1996 totalled 42,172 tons, a drop of 29.24 percent with
respect to the previous season, said the Argentine Wool Federation.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's Foreign Currency Reserves Drop 5 Percent
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's foreign currency reserves dropped 5
percent in March compared with the previous month to 54.331
billion dollars, said the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Altamir Lopes, chief of the Economic Department of the central
bank said that the drop in the reserves was due to the
restrictions adopted by the government to halt the entry of
dollars used for speculation.
</P>
<P>
Brazil to Import 11 Million Tons of Coal
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil will import 11 million tons of coal
worth 650 million dollars this year for its steel industry. Of
the total, 3 million tons will come from the United States and the
remainder from Colombia, China and others countries.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is short of coal and therefore many of its steel
factories depend on imports for operation.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela's Foreign Investments Reach 74.5 Million Dollars in
</P>
<P>
1st Quarter
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela received 74.526 million dollars of foreign
capital during the first quarter of the year, an increase of 5
percent over the same period in 1995, said the Superintendent's
Office of Foreign Investments (SIEX).
</P>
<P>
The biggest amount of investments was reported in January with
48 million dollars while the sum of 11.9 million dollars received
in March was the first to show a down-turn trend compared with the
same period in 1995, said the SIEX.
</P>
<P>
Colombia's Ecopetrol to Invest One Billion Dollars in 1996
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Ecopetrol, Colombia's state-owned
petroleum company, will invest one billion dollars this year to
promote petroleum exploration activities in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the oil company, the explorations
will intensify in the eastern part of Colombia over an area of
1,300 square kilometers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
