<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norway Urges Meeting on Third World Social Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Norway called on an
international conference today to improve basic social services in
the developing nations, according to reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Norwegian Overseas Development Minister Kari Nordheim-Larsen,
speaking at the start of a three-day meeting here, said the
conference should build on commitments made at a United Nations
social summit in Copenhagen last year.
</P>
<P>
About 120 delegates from 40 countries and organizations are
attending the meeting, on which they will discuss a follow-up to
some aspects of the Copenhagen summit.
</P>
<P>
Nordheim-Larsen said a so-called "20-20" formula, agreed in
Copenhagen, should help the Third World countries and their
industrialized partners to fulfill the commitments made on last
year's summit.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that by the end of this meeting we will be
able to demonstrate our readiness to translate the commitment we
made in Copenhagen into concrete terms," she said.
</P>
<P>
The "20-20" formula requires that 20 percent of development aid
be allocated to basic social programs while the recipient nation
in return spend 20 percent of its national budget on social needs.
</P>
<P>
However, Tanzanian Foreign Minister Jakaya Mrisho Kikwete
sounded notes of caution, saying that developing countries
suffering heavy debt burdens may have difficulties to achieve that
goal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
