<HEADLINE> India May Get Interest-free Loan from IDA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- India is likely to get an
interest-free loan of about 3.5 billion US dollars over the next
three years, beginning July, in the recently approved 11th
replenishment of the International Development Association (IDA),
the Patriot reported today.
</P>
<P>
An indication to this effect was given by the Indian delegation
led by Finance Secretary Montek Singh Ahluwalia after its meeting
in Washington with World Bank President James Wolfenson Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
Delegation sources said India's share in the IDA-11, the
concessionary lending agency of the World Bank, would be almost
equal to what it had in IDA-10. India received 3.8 billion
dollars in IDA-10.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has not formally decided on IDA allocations.
Only last month, some 30 donor countries had agreed to the IDA-11
replenishment of about 22 billion dollars over the next three
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
