<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Finds Alarming Lack of Fitness Among Chinese Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, April 24 (Xinhua)-- The sports grounds on Chinese
campuses seem to be more or less deserted these days, as a survey
indicates that more than half of Chinese university students take
no exercise whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
Although many young students can get worked up about spectator
sports and spectaculars such as the Olympic Games, they pay far
from enough attention to their own physical exercise.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the Public Opinion Research Institute
of the People's University here, shows that most students spend
their spare time "chatting" and "doing the assignments" instead of
taking part in sports.
</P>
<P>
Ball games are still popular on campuses, but sports such as
running and callisthenics are now almost forgotten by large
numbers of students.
</P>
<P>
Again, according to the survey, only 14 percent of students
take some kind of exercise every day. Moreover, their number has
been steadily shrinking in recent years. The survey finds that the
number of students engaging in physical exercise shrank by about
30 percent last year, compared with 1994.
</P>
<P>
The survey stresses that the situation for female students and
graduate students is even more deplorable. Ten percent more
female students than male students "seldom" exercise.
</P>
<P>
The location of the universities is also found to have some
influence on whether students do physical exercises. The number of
students who do physical exercises regularly is smaller in
universities located in more-developed regions than in those in
less-developed regions, the survey notes.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Liu Xiayang, who supervised the survey, said that the
survey highlights the urgency of the related departments to make
efforts to increase students' awareness of the importance of
physical exercise.
</P>
<P>
"I really worry about the situation, and something must be done
immediately," said Liu, who is also the deputy director of the
research institute.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Beijing University, one of the nation's
leading universities, has launched some regulations to encourage
students to take more physical exercise.
</P>
<P>
According to Li Anmo, vice-president of Beijing University,
besides two hours of physical education weekly, the students are
also required to master a sport such as swimming.
</P>
<P>
"We aim to make our students able to work healthily for society
for 50 years," the vice-president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
