<HEADLINE> Roundup: Southern Africa Enters New Era Of Peace, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 24 (Xinhua)-- Countries in southern Africa have
concentrated their efforts on economic development and seeking of
suitable development patterns in recent years after acquisition of
peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The southern African region, which had been beset by
disturbances for more than a dozen years, has ushered in the new
era after realizing peace and stability in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the region has witnessed the birth of a new
South Africa, the successful holding of general elections in
Mozambique following the end of a 16-year-long civil war, the
remarkable progress in Angola's peace process, and the
achievement of gradual political stability in other
countries in the region after experiencing upheavals caused by
transition to multi-party system.
</P>
<P>
Peace and stability in the region have provided more
favorable conditions than ever before for regional economic
development and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The southern African countries should seize the opportunity for
economic development as the region had entered the era of peace and
stability, pointed out a communique issued by the 1995 Annual Summit
of the Southern African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
Under the new situation, the countries in the region are
implementing various economic reform policies with a view to
resuscitating and promoting their respective economies.
</P>
<P>
South Africa recorded a three-percent economic growth rate last
year, the highest in the past 10 years, as a result of the
implementation of the reconstruction and development scheme. Its
volume of trade with other African countries has increased by 50
percent since the lifting of the United Nations sanctions against it.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has made positive results in the economic reforms,
registering an annual economic growth rate of some four percent in
the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Namibia and Botswana have progressed steadily, due to their
suitable policies since independence. Namibia's economy has
been developing at an average annual rate of 3.5 percent in the
past five year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
