<HEADLINE> Disease Threatens Shrimp Industry in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A highly contagious disease, which
has no cure or treatment, is threatening Bangladesh's shrimp
industry as large numbers of shrimp are dying of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Directorate of Fisheries (DOF) said here today
that the disease, identified as "white spot" disease, has most
recently hit shrimp cultivation in the greater Khulna area,
southwest of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The disease, which attacks salt water shrimp such as "bagda"
(black tiger shrimp), has never occurred before in such a
widespread manner in the shrimp farms of this country, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Fishery officials are almost certain that the disease was
brought in along with shrimp fry imported from Thailand and other
countries.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates by the Department of Fisheries, two
thirds of the 30,000 hectares under bagda cultivation in Satkhira
district, and nearly half of the 28,000 hectares in Khulna
district have already been infected by the "white spot" disease.
</P>
<P>
Affected shrimp normally die before reaching marketable size.
</P>
<P>
Losses in export of bagda, which accounts for approximately 70
percent of all shrimp produced in the country, could amount to
over 150 million US dollars, industry exports said.
</P>
<P>
Shrimp industry, the third largest export industry in
Bangladesh, totally earned over 250 million dollars in 1994-95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
