<HEADLINE> Overseas Airlines Expand China Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The US Northwest Airlines will
open a new flight to China on May 3. The Detroit-Beijing flight
will be the company's first non-stop one between the US and China.
</P>
<P>
The US carrier at present operates three flights a week between
the US and China via Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
With China's increasing popularity as a tourist destination,
said Christine Betzer, Beijing-based sales manager for Northwest,
there is growing demand for more routes and services to China.
</P>
<P>
Alfred W. Brader, China manager for Austrian Airlines,
estimated that the number of Austrian tourists to China tripled in
the one year since Austrian Airlines opened the first
Vienna-Beijing route last March.
</P>
<P>
Brader said his company is seeking to expand its services to
Beijing and open new ones to other Chinese cities such as
Shanghai, and "we expect to have three flights a week to Beijing
next year".
</P>
<P>
Singapore Airlines has increased the number of its flights to
Beijing from the original seven to ten a week since March 31.
</P>
<P>
More carriers have recently obtained approval from China's
civil aviation authorities for new routes or flights to the
country.
</P>
<P>
Air Macao, which already operates two routes from Macao to
Beijing and Shanghai, is soon to start a new service to Xiamen,
while Royal Dutch Airlines plans to open its first China route in
June, according to the Civil Aviation Administration of China
(CAAC).
</P>
<P>
The CAAC has so far granted approval to 47 overseas carriers to
operate China services, including many of the world's leading ones
such as United Airlines, Lufthansa and Scandinavian Airlines.
</P>
<P>
China currently boasts an annual growth rate of over 20 percent
in air traffic, one of the highest in the world, and has
established air links with nearly 40 countries, according to the
CAAC.  
</P>
