<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Trade System Faced with Major Challenges: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The convergence of regionalism
and multilateralism is a main challenge facing the world
multilateral trading system, Renato Ruggiero, director-general of
the World Trade Organization (WTO) said here today, stressing the
need for governments around the world to respond to the
challenges.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the two-day World Trade Congress, which opened here
today, Ruggiero said that as they consider the points on the
first WTO Ministerial Conference agenda, governments should also
have in mind the need to respond to three major challenges which
confront the multilateral system as the world approaches the new
century.
</P>
<P>
He said the main challenge is to ensure that national barriers
are not just replaced by regional ones, but that, on the contrary,
regionalism and multilateralism converge at the end of the road.
</P>
<P>
"I see this as the main challenge facing the multilateral
system at present, one which will shape its future and help shape
the world of the 21st century," he commented.
</P>
<P>
Another challenge facing the multilateral system, as the WTO
Chief outlined, is to respect and strengthen the fundamental
contract that now unites countries at all levels of economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The industrialized world has to keep open its markets and
improve their openness in the years ahead, while the developing
countries have to continue with their liberalizing reforms and
increase their integration into the global system, he explained.
</P>
<P>
The third challenge, Ruggiero pointed out, is to accept the
shared responsibility, shared among existing WTO members and those
countries wishing to become members, for constructing what he
described as "a truly universal system which all the present and
future candidate can join in and contribute to."
</P>
<P>
Nearly 700 participants, including government ministers, senior
officials, eminent businessmen and prominent academicians from
Asia, America, and Europe, are attending the two-day World Trade
Congress, co-organized by the Singapore Trade Development Board
(TDB) and the International Herald Tribune, to discuss issues
related to the evolution and efficacy of the 120-member WTO.
</P>
<P>
Barry Desker, chief executive office of the TDB, said the
inputs from the private sector and academia at the Congress would
be compiled to be used as a reference for the first WTO
Ministerial Conference, to be held in Singapore in December this
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
