<HEADLINE> Panama Won't Negotiate With U.S. Over Bases: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Panama has for now ruled out
any negotiations with the U.S. over the future of its military
bases in the country after the year 2000, President Ernesto Perez
Balladares said today.
</P>
<P>
But he didn't close the door completely to talks and said there
was still the possibility of exploring the issue at the request of
the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian president also promised to consult the nation
about any agreement to prolong the U.S. military presence in
Panama.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on his recent three-nation
European tour, Balladares dismissed any connection between the
continuation of U.S. bases and the war against drugs
trafficking. He said the government is determined to continue the
war against drugs "with or without the North Americans."
</P>
<P>
The United States has eight military bases and some 7,500
troops in Panama. It is due to return the Panama Canal to
Panamanian rule and withdraw all its troops from the country by
December 31, 1999, under a treaty signed by the two countries in
1977.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is seeking to keep a military presence in Panama after
the handover. But talks were suspended in November 1995 as the
two sides failed to agree on leasing fees for the U.S. bases.
</P>
<P>
President Balladeres' tour of Belgium, Italy and France earlier
in April was partly aimed at assuring users of the canal about its
future after the U.S. handover in 1999 and encouraging European
investment in the canal zones.
</P>
<P>
The President also signed an agreement with some of Panama's
international bank creditors to restructure its debts, which
should lead to a 30 percent reduction in repayments amounting to
some one billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
