<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ESCAP Moves to Fewer Meetings: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Executive Secretary of ESCAP
Adrianus Mooy said today the organization is moving to reduce the
number of meetings it organizes each year as part of its reform
program.
</P>
<P>
Mooy also said that the United Nations Economic and Social
Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) will also improve the
quality of its publications so that they become more informative
and be of more value to its members.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to a statement made on Tuesday by US
ambassador to Thailand, William Itoh, to the ongoing ESCAP 52nd
Session, which closes later today.
</P>
<P>
The US ambassador urged ESCAP to speed up reform, "meet less
and do more," and "eliminate some programs to reinvest in new,
more relevant activities."
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to expect a cost-effective, well-organized ESCAP
that addresses the high-priority issues of its members while
eliminating those activities determined to be of marginal value,"
the US statement said.
</P>
<P>
In response, Mooy said that the US statement has focused on
reform only, which is one of the crises the UN system is facing.
The other crisis is lack of funding.
</P>
<P>
The US is under widespread criticism for failing in making its
financial contributions to the 185-member United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Of the 2.9 billion dollars owed by member states to the UN, the
US share is 1.2 billion dollars, Mooy said.
</P>
<P>
"The two are very closely related.... We need a certain degree
of financial stability if we are to carry out reform," Mooy said.
</P>
<P>
ESCAP has set April 1997, its 50th anniversary, as the target
date for completion of the strategy for overall reform of the
organization, which now has 50 full members and 10 associate
members in the Asia-Pacific region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
