<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Report: Public Spending Cuts Affect Education Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Public spending cuts often eat
away at education spending in some of the world's poorest nations,
a United Nations specialized agency said today.
</P>
<P>
The findings, by the Geneva-based International Labor
Organization (ILO), were made public with the release of a report
prepared for a meeting of educational experts.
</P>
<P>
"Most countries spend much of their government budgets on
schooling and a very high fraction of educational spending goes
for teachers' salaries," according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it said, cuts in public spending have "major
implications for education and teachers."
</P>
<P>
In addition, pressure to reduce overall spending often lead
governments to cut education spending, the report said, adding
that education budget has seen almost no rise in the poorest
countries.
</P>
<P>
"The negative impact on education was particularly harmful
because an improvement in labor force skills was vital in view of
new goods, services and production procedures needed to compete
and stimulate growth in the 80s and 90s," it concluded.
</P>
<P>
The ILO also criticized the World Bank and International
Monetary Fund for imposing policies on developing countries that
make reducing public spending an important condition for loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
