<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank to Curb Credit Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand, the
country's central bank, will step up its control of credit
extensions by foreign bank branches and finance companies in a
fresh move to rein in inflation and the current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
In July, finance companies will be subject to a 0.5 percent
rise in the capital requirement to 7.5 percent covering the
capital to risk-weight assets ratio, according to Bank Governor
Vijit Supinit.
</P>
<P>
The increased ratio, in addition to the five monetary measures
launched recently, will strengthen the banks and finance
companies' positions and help curb inflation and the current
account deficit.
</P>
<P>
Previous orders include the requirement that banks increase
their capital-to-risk asset ratio to 8.5 percent from 8 percent
and foreign banks from 6.75 percent to 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Regarding credit growth control, Vijit did not specify the
amount, but said the loan-to-deposit (LTD) ratios of finance
companies and foreign branches should be lowered.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand sees the revision necessary as the
companies have extended large amounts of credit to the real estate
sector. However, the LTD control is expected to aggravate the
negative impact of the banks' operations, directly affecting their
lending capacities, according to insiders.
</P>
<P>
The LTD control will mainly disturb banks which rely largely on
overseas funds and focus on retail banking.
</P>
<P>
The move is likely to slow down short-term capital inflows,
which now account for 70 percent of the total influx.
</P>
<P>
Currently the LTD of finance companies is 130 percent. Last
year, their credit growth reached 25.4 percent, lower than the
29.6 percent expected.
</P>
<P>
This year, the target has been revised down due to declining
outstanding credits totaling one trillion baht (40 billion U.S.
dollars), or one fourth of the banking system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Ready to Join ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Cambodian King Norodom
Sihanouk said today his country would follow France's advice to
join the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the king at a lunch with Prime Minister Alain Juppe
on the second day of his three-day state visit expressed his
personal reluctance to the regional alliance.
</P>
<P>
"I was never for ASEAN, I am for total independence, a neutral
Cambodia," he said.
</P>
<P>
In explaining Cambodia's decision to move closer toward ASEAN,
the 73-year-old king said: "As I am a francophile and France
said 'go-ahead, join,' then I will."
</P>
<P>
"France gives solidarity with the rest of Europe as an example,
it wants us to do the same," Sihanouk added.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia, like Laos, is expected to join ASEAN, which groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand
and Vietnam, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sihanouk arrived in France on Friday for a three-day private
stay before going on official. The visit is his first outside
Asia since returning to the throne in 1993.
</P>
<P>
It's also the first state visit to France by any foreign leader
since President Jacques Chirac took office 11 months ago.
</P>
<P>
France, the former colonial power in Southeast Asia, is the
second aid donor to Phnom Penh after Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
