<HEADLINE> France Ready to Join New NATO Military Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- France is ready to take part in
a "new military structure" in NATO, the country's top military
officer said today after taking part in its first meeting of
the alliance's military committee for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
"The notion of an integrated military structure no longer
exists ... from now on we speak of a new structure or of a future
structure." Jean-Philippe Douin told reporters after the meeting
of the chiefs-of-staff of NATO's 16 members.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was the first attended by France since 1966
when the then President Charles de Gaulle pulled the country out
NATO's integrated military structure complaining of
U.S. domination.
</P>
<P>
France, which announced last December it was moving closer to
NATO's military wing, has been one of the most vocal supporters of
a stronger European voice in the alliance, one of the reforms now
being debated by NATO chiefs.
</P>
<P>
Douin said that if NATO reform went ahead, there were no
obstacles he could foresee to full French participation.
</P>
<P>
But, he added, "Either the new structure will be adopted or it
will not be. If it will not be, we will not come."  
