<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNESCO Report: World Science Need More Money, More Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations report suggests
that nations around the world should spend at least 0.4 percent of
their gross national product (GNP) on research and development by
2000, and let more women get into laboratories.
</P>
<P>
World Science Report 1996, released today by the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), says
that many countries, especially those in the developing world, are
not spending enough money on science research.
</P>
<P>
Many young women are refused or discouraged to enter the
research circles, both because of the stubborn sex barriers that
long prevail in many nations and because women get less salaries
than their male colleagues, the report says.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Japan lead the world in spending on
science at 2.8 percent of GNP, followed by the 15-member European
Union (EU) with an average spending of 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
But in developing countries, most nations spend their limited
capital on raising people's living standards and creating new
market and jobs.
</P>
<P>
"Although there is almost universal support for this idea of
science as an engine of economic and social improvement ... in
many parts of the world there is still a lack of political
commitment to science,'' said UNESCO Director-General Federico
Mayor.
</P>
<P>
Russia, a traditionally science leader, could risk undermining
its drive toward a market economy by slashing science spending at
an unprecedented low level of 0.8 percent of GNP -- roughly the
same as Iceland and Ireland, observers pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Since many developing nations cannot afford high costs on
science research, the gap between them and the developed countries
could be widened, some critics expressed their worries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
