<HEADLINE> Czechs Pull Down Finland at World Ice Hockey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Republic upset Finland
4-2 in Group B on Tuesday, keeping the defending champions away
from their first win at the World Ice Hockey Championship.
</P>
<P>
Forward Robert Lang opened the scoring for the Czechs with 8:36
into the first period before Juha Riihijaervi netted the equaliser
with four minutes into the second period.
</P>
<P>
Yet, Frantisek Kaberle put the Czechs ahead anew when he was
left unchecked and slided home in front of the net. Viktor Ujcik
added a third near the end of the second period.
</P>
<P>
With six minutes to play, Teemu Selanne pulled Finland back to
within one.
</P>
<P>
Since then the Czech goalie blocked all the attacks from the
Finns, while Jiri Kucera kicked home the last into an empty net.
</P>
<P>
In the day's other games, the United States and Italy kept
their records intact with respective wins over Germany and Norway,
while Canada overcame the hosts Austria with ease. 
</P>
