<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long Cold Winter Affects Poland's Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The extremely long and cold winter
which has just passed inflicted heavy losses on Poland's
agriculture, the Ministry of Agriculture said.
</P>
<P>
About 66 percent of rape, 42 percent of winter barley and 6
percent of winter wheat were destroyed because of the severe
cold. The agricultural provinces such as Skierniewice, Gorzow and
Warsaw were worst hit.
</P>
<P>
Experts said those crops which had survived the freezing season
may face an impending drought triggered by the belated spring. So
there would be an inevitable reduction in the output.
</P>
<P>
The Polish government said the output cut would surely lead to
a rise in the prices of agricultural products and called on all
departments to make concerted efforts to reduce the decrease to the
minimum.
</P>
<P>
To relieve the heavy burden put on farmers by the price surge,
the government would provide low-interest loans for them and
increase the circulating fund they would spend on seeds,
fertilizers, fuels and agricultural chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said that some 150,000 farmers got low-interest
loans in the first two months of this year and that there would be
more applicants for the loans in the coming months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
