<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Trade Congress Opens in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The World Trade Congress opened
here today with Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong urging the
World Trade Organization (WTO) to view regional initiatives as
markers or leading indicators of the achievable.
</P>
<P>
Regional trade arrangements, rather than posing a threat to the
multilateral trading system, are the building blocs of trade
infrastructure, Goh said.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of regional ventures undertaken by the OECD, APEC,
and ASEAN on trade and investment, can form the basis of
discussions, or even negotiations, within the WTO at a future
date, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The WTO should view regional initiatives as markers or leading
indicators of the achievable," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized that the WTO's agenda must adapt to the
changing global environment, and to the pace set by the regional
trading arrangements.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise, it risks becoming marginalized and irrelevant to
the business community," he warned.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 700 participants, including government ministers, senior
officials, eminent businessmen and prominent academicians from
Asia, America, and Europe, are attending the two-day World Trade
Congress, co-organized by the Singapore Trade Development Board
(TDB) and the International Herald Tribune.
</P>
<P>
Barry Desker, chief executive officer of the TDB, said the
inputs from the private sector and academia at the Congress would
be compiled to be used as a reference for the first WTO
Ministerial Conference, to be held in Singapore in December this
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
