<HEADLINE> Thailand's First Commercial Fleet Under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Office of the Maritime
Promotion Committee (OMPC) of Thailand has finalized terms for
forming a joint venture with the state-owned Thai Maritime
Navigation (TMN) to build Thailand's first commercial fleet.
</P>
<P>
A key requirement in the terms for private investors was that
the prospective partner must be a shipping company with Thais
holding more than 70 of the shares, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
Any bidder must have at least five years' navigation and
maritime business experience and have more than five vessels with
a total capacity of over 50,000 deadweight tons, the committee
added.
</P>
<P>
Bidders must submit a five-year development plan to the TMN,
which must correspond with the country's 1996-2006 maritime
promotion plan.
</P>
<P>
The prospective partner must also be prepared to expand the
fleet to at least seven vessels within five years, with a total
capacity of at least 100,000 deadweight tons, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
If the TMN board approves the terms on May 13, the Transport
and Communications Ministry would consider pricing of the TMN
shares, the committee said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
