<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Government Denies Presidential Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian
government today denied a report in the Barcelona-based La
Vanguardia newspaper that President Ernesto Samper had considered
stepping down as a solution to a political crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The president has not contemplated stepping down from power as
a solution to the political crisis; if this were the most
convenient solution for the country, it would already have been
taken," Secretary General to the President Jose Antonio Vargas
Lleras said in a letter to La Vanguardia.
</P>
<P>
Samper, publicly criticized for receiving funds from the Cali
drug cartel in his 1994 presidential election campaign, is now
under investigation by the House Accusation Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Barcelona newspaper wrote that, doubting the results of the
investigations and the political crisis, Samper wanted to resign
from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Vargas noted in the letter that the La Vanguardia said
"inexplicably, and without any proof" that Samper "had already
decided to resign and that he was supposedly negotiating with the
vice president the conditions for his withdrawal from the
government."
</P>
<P>
"To that respect I hereby declare," added the letter, "that
this information is completely false."
</P>
<P>
He continued that "the truth is that the honorable Chamber of
Representatives has ended the investigation process and we are
certain that this process will terminate by reiterating the
innocence of the chief executive."
</P>
<P>
Vargas pointed out that Samper himself has said at the end of
the process in the House that he himself will present the country
with a solution to the current political crisis.
</P>
<P>
"What is happening is that some adversaries of the government
in Colombia confuse a solution to the crisis with the president's
departure, in which, of course, they are also mistaken," he
explained.
</P>
<P>
Samper submitted to questioning before the House Accusation
Committee today for the third time in less than 6 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
