<HEADLINE> Honda to Make Thailand its Regional Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- With the inauguration today of a
new Honda plant in Ayutthaya, 80 kilometers north of the capital,
the Japanese auto maker aims to make Thailand a regional center
for its ASEAN market.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, Honda controls the second biggest share of the
passenger car market after Toyota and the new plant plays a
crucial role in its complementary parts supply strategy in the
region covered by the Association of the Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
The 120-million-U.S. dollar-plant in Ayutthaya will produce and
export auto parts to support production and sales of the Honda
"City" compact cars in Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
The "City" compact, which was launched in Bangkok Tuesday, is
designed and manufactured especially for the Asian market.
</P>
<P>
Honda expects the sales of all three Honda models -- the Civic,
Accord and City -- in Thailand to total about 45,000 units this
year, and it aims to become the number one in the passenger car
segment with annual sales of 60,000 units by 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
