<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Expert in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Although she is Russian, she has
devoted herself to agricultural education and scientific research
in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region for nearly
50 years.
</P>
<P>
She is one of the more than 10,000 Russians now living in
Xinjiang, all of them descendants of people who have come from
Russia since the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
Valitina Tubanova, a professor at Xinjiang Agricultural
University, is one of the most outstanding, and has had a number
of noteworthy achievements in plant cultivation.
</P>
<P>
Tubanova does research on saussurea, a genus of herbs found
mainly in temperate and cool regions, and has successfully
propagated it through tissue cultures.
</P>
<P>
Several dozens of saussurea, grown on her experimental plots
for four years, are expected to be planted outdoor next year.
</P>
<P>
Tubanova is also a master of the Russian, Chinese and Uygur
languages. She became a teacher at the Xinjiang Agricultural
University after graduating from college and has worked there for
more than 30 years. Of her several thousands of students, many
have become agricultural specialists.
</P>
<P>
She did not halt her research when she retired in 1989, but
went on to make several discoveries in plant tissue culture.
</P>
<P>
Her research on potatoes helped solve virus and storage
problems.
</P>
<P>
She did successful research on wild licorice tissue culture,
which provided technology for afforestation of sandy areas in the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
What she worries about most is that many hi-tech achievements
cannot be used because of lack of funds, "I can't let my
achievements stay in the laboratory, I want to contribute more to
the state."
</P>
<P>
Tubanova is also active in political affairs. She has been a
member of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Regional Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference since 1982, and
acted as a Standing Committee member of the regional CPPCC
committee for nine years.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade or more, she has put forward a series of
proposals on building Russian schools, and enrolling Russian
college students.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangxi to Develop Railway Towns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Jiangxi Province in east China
will spend one billion yuan on the development of small towns
along the Beijing-Kowloon Railway, which runs 707 km across the
province.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said the money will be spent on 100 towns and
100 villages which are models of rural housing, and the training
of technicians and skilled workers for the towns.
</P>
<P>
The province now has 200-odd small towns, most of which are in
the vicinity of major highways or railways.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-Kowloon Railway, which is expected to open by the
end of the year, runs through 22 counties and cities in Jiangxi,
which hold 25 percent of the province's total area and 30 percent
of its population. It will have 55 stations in Jiangxi.
</P>
<P>
The officials believe that the railway will bring them a
valuable chance to develop the local economy.
</P>
<P>
These towns will eventually become important bases for the
production and processing of farm products and raw materials as
well as other industries, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
