<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Clubs Fined for Fan Riots in European Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 23 (Xinhua) -- More soccer clubs have been fined
by the UEFA for the riots of their fans in the European Cup
competitions, the European soccer governing body said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Real Madrid was fined for 105,000 Swiss francs (85,000 US
dollars) for the riots of its fans in the European Cup
quarter-final second leg match on March 20 against Juventus.
</P>
<P>
Juventus was fined 15,000 francs (12,200 US dollars) for
"setting off fireworks and organisational shortcomings" at the
same match in Turin.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Juventus was also fined 40,000 francs (32,500 US
dollars) for fan fireworks and riots in another match on April 3.
</P>
<P>
Then, the fans of Juventus again set off fireworks and eight of
them even invaded to the pitch when their club played against
Nantes in the European Cup semifinal first leg match.
</P>
<P>
Nantes was fined 10,000 francs (8,100 US dollars) for improper
conduct at the return match in France on April 17.
</P>
<P>
Nantes player Bruno Carotti was banned for two games after
being sent off.
</P>
<P>
Other clubs fined included Greece's Panathinaikos whose fans
also threw fireworks into the pitch in another semifinal against
Ajax Amsterdam, the UEFA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
