<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong's Telecom Market Expanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province,
one of the richest local economies in the country, is expected to
see a huge demand for telecommunications network equipment and
terminal products over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xuedao, deputy director of the Guangdong Posts and
Telecommunications Bureau, said that the province needs more than
four million telephones every year. Other telecom terminal
products, including modems, broad-band and narrow-band interface
equipment, and multimedia terminals will also see swelling sales
in the near future.
</P>
<P>
But the traditional small switches without integrated functions
will lose their market share soon.
</P>
<P>
The localization rate of telecom equipment will be improved,
with the program-controlled switching systems manufactured by
joint ventures and domestic enterprises gradually replacing the
dominance of foreign brands in China's telecom market.
</P>
<P>
The province will invest 15 billion yuan (about 1.8 billion US
dollars) in the telecom industry this year, not including
handsets, mobile phones and modems, according to the "People's
Posts and Telecommunications Daily".
</P>
<P>
So far, Guangdong has the most complete telecommunications
system in China, boasting a telephone switching capacity of 20
million lines and 13 million telephone users. Its telephone
density reached 24 percent, and the switching capacity of mobile
phone network stands at four million channels.
</P>
<P>
The province will shift its focus to the development of a
large-capacity digital transmission network and broad-band
intelligent service this year. By the end of this century, a
high-speed broad-band telecommunications network will take shape
in the Pearl River Delta, the richest region of Guangdong, laying
a foundation for the construction of the "information
superhighway" in the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajikistan Seeks Investment from Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Tajikistan hopes that Thailand
could invest in its energy and gold and coal mining industries, a
Tajik official said here.
</P>
<P>
Makhmudov Isroil, first deputy minister for economy and foreign
relations of Tajikistan, who was on an official visit to Thailand,
met with Thai Deputy Industry Minister Anusorn Wongwan in Bangkok
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Anusorn told Isroil that Tajikistan has a good potential as an
investment haven thanks to the availability of natural resources
and low wages in the country.
</P>
<P>
Many factories in Tajikistan have closed down following the
departure of Russians since it gained independence from Moscow in
1991, he said.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that investment in Tajikistan might be
problematic because of the political instability and lack of good
transportation. There is also no direct flight to and from
Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Anusorn said the Tajik official also hoped that the Thai
government could open a direct flight from Bangkok.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
