<HEADLINE> German Soldiers Indicted for Extreme-Right Offenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-three German soldiers were
convicted of extreme right-wing offenses last year, mostly for
using or displaying symbols of banned rightist organizations.
</P>
<P>
But the government doesn't believe the convictions are a sign
of a growing extreme-right trend in the army, as the soldiers
account for less than 0.2 percent of the total, a parliamentary
report said today.
</P>
<P>
The number of offenders in 1995 is higher than the 1994 figure
of 43, but lower than the 63 soldiers convicted in 1993 for
radical right-wing offenses. 
</P>
