<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechen Rebel Leader's Death Yet to Be Confirmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The death of Chechen separatist
leader Dzhokhar Dudayev in Russian troops' missile strike on
Tuesday is yet to be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
According to the Itar-Tass news agency, Dudayev's former chief
negotiator at talks with Moscow, Khozh-Akhmed Yarikhanov, said
earlier today that Dudayev was killed late on April 21.
</P>
<P>
Yarikhanov said that he had seen "Dudayev's dead body with his
own eyes." He also said that Dudayev's former deputy Zelimkhan
Yandarbiyev, former Vice President of the Chechen Republic of
Ichkeria, had succeeded as the head of the republic.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass quoted the government of Ichkeria as saying that
Russian troops' missile strike hit the working emplacement of
Dudayev on the evening of April 21, when he was conversing by
satellite telephone with the mediator about conditions for talks
with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
As a result, he was seriously wounded and died on the same day
in the village of Gekhi Chu, 30 kilometers southwest of the
Chechen capital of Grozny, Itar-Tass said, adding that some of his
closest associates had died together.
</P>
<P>
However, a number of high-ranking Chechen separatist officials
have denied reports on Dudayev's death, the Interfax news agency
reported tonight.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted Saipudi Khasanov, personal secretary of Dudayev
as saying that the Chechen separatist leader "is alive and working
as usual."
</P>
<P>
Interfax also quoted one of Dudayev's followers in an overseas
office as saying that he received a satellite phone call from
Dudayev at about 17:00 Moscow time (GMT 15:00) today and they
discussed normal business. He said the reports of Dudayev's death
are a provocation and totally untrue.
</P>
<P>
According to Interfax, Khasan Khazuyev, Deputy Prime Minister
in Dudayev's separatist government, has dismissed as "bluff" the
reports that Dudayev was killed.
</P>
<P>
"Should this happen, I would be the first to learn that because
I have direct contacts with Dudayev," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Abdulla Bugayev, First Deputy Prime Minister of the
Moscow-backed Chechen government told the Interfax that he has no
information proving the death of Dudayev.
</P>
<P>
"Rumors about the murder of the separatist leader are indeed
circulating in the republic, but all of them are based solely on
media reports," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, official representatives of the Russian troops
command told the Interfax tonight that they were unaware of the
death of Dudayev.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass reports said that the Russian government announced
that it had received no word whatsoever from formal sources which
could confirm the rebel leader's death.
</P>
<P>
Dudayev, 51, has led an armed resistance against the Russian
forces in the breakaway republic of Chechnya for over 16
months. The conflict has left over 30,000 people dead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
