<HEADLINE> Bruguera Wins First-Rounder in Monte Carlo Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Despite an operation on foot last
year, Sergi Bruguera won two straight sets for his opener at the
Monte Carlo Tennis Open on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Against Italian Andrea Gaudenzi, the 25-year-old Spaniard won
6-2, 7-6 in one hour 23 minutes on a sheltered court at the
Country Club in Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
Despite his victory, the ninth-seeded Spaniard said he need
more wins to boost his morale on the court.
</P>
<P>
Bruguera won the Open twice in 1991 and 1993, once ruled on the
clay court in 1993 and 1994, acknowledged that he was still not a
rival for newly crowned clay-court king Thomas Muster of Austria.
</P>
<P>
Against Gaudenzi, Bruguera rushed ahead 3-0 in the second set
before the 1995 semifinalist rallied to 4-4.
</P>
<P>
In the only tie-break, Bruguera won 7-3 with powerful
baseliners.
</P>
<P>
Bruguera dropped out of the top ten in the world due to the
injury sustained in 1994 when he won the French Open for the
second time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
