<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Pleased with Agreement in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 23 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali is extremely pleased to learn that a
cease-fire agreement was reached today in Yamoussoukro, Cote
D'Ivoire between the government of Sierra Leone and the
Revolutional United Front, said a U.N. spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Closing two days of talks under the auspices of the United
Nations and the Government of Cote d'Ivoire, the two sides agreed
to continue cessation of hostilities with a view to creating a
climate of confidence conducive to the conclusion of a peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
"On this auspicious occasion, the Secretary-General wishes to
express to the Government of Cote d'Ivoire, and in particular to
President Henri Konan Bedie, his deep gratitude for their support
to the mediation efforts of his Special Envoy, Berhanu Dinka,
which contributed to the successful conclusion of these talks,"
said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general hoped that the agreement reached in
Yamoussoukro will mark a new beginning for lasting peace in Sierra
Leone, the spokesman added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
