<HEADLINE> World Bank-Funded Irrigation Project in Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A World Bank-funded irrigation
project has gone into operation in north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region after seven years of construction.
</P>
<P>
The project was built by inviting bids from both inside and
outside China with 66 million US dollars-worth of loans provided
by the World Bank. It includes eight trunk canals covering a total
area of 345,000 ha.
</P>
<P>
The project has brought 40,000 ha of arid land under irrigation
and improved 100,000 ha of medium- and low-yield fields,
increasing the grain output by 80 million kg.  
</P>
</TEXT>
