<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian PA Calls on Government to Expel Israeli Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Deputies of Egypt's People's
Assembly (PA) today called on the government to expel Israel's
ambassador and recall its own ambassador to Israel to protest
against Israel's attacks on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The official Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported that at a
parliamentary session focused on Israel's aggression on south
Lebanon, the deputies also asked Jordan to follow Egypt's example
and urged an immediate suspension of all Arab steps to normalize
relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The call came amid mounting anger in the Arab and Moslem world
over Israel's 13-day campaign in retaliation for Iran-backed
Hezbollah guerrillas' shelling in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Since the hostilities began, more than 100 people have been
killed, most of them Lebanese civilians.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PA Speaker Ahmed Fathi Sorour announced at the end
of the session that no People's Assembly delegation will be
allowed to visit Israel at present.
</P>
<P>
"The parliament is the voice of the people. So long as the
people are angry with Israel, no representatives of the people
will travel to Israel to talk with those who chose the language of
war and preferred it over that of peace," Sorour said.
</P>
<P>
He added that no parliamentarians will visit Israel until the
peace process is resumed.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian delegation was scheduled to travel to Israel
according to a decision taken by the parliamentary executive
committee within the framework of the dialogue to realize a just
and all-out regional peace, according to Sorour.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was the first Arab country to establish diplomatic ties
with Israel, but relations between the two sides have stayed cool,
even in comparatively peaceful times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960424.0287 </DOCNO>
