<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ski Trial Concluded at German Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Prosecutors have decided to accept
the compensation money on Tuesday, ending a case against two
International Ski Federation (FIS) officials over the death of
Ulrike Maier.
</P>
<P>
At the court in Munich, the prosecutors agreed to an offer of
600,000 Swiss francs (490,000 US dollars), despite the two FIS
officials Jan Tischhauser of Switzerland and Kurt Hoch of Austria
pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
The money would be paid to Maier's six-year-old daughter
Melanie.
</P>
<P>
Maier, double world super giant slalom champion, was killed in
1994 when she broke her neck after hitting a post in a World Cup
downhill race at Garmisch-Partenkirchen in Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
