<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgrade Police Arrests Mosque Bombing Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Belgrade police has arrested two
persons on suspicion of planting explosives outside religious
buildings and under cars in the 1992-1994 period, a police
statement said today.
</P>
<P>
Aleksandar Gajic, aged 34, and Milan Dobrilovic, aged 33, are
suspected of planting an explosive device in the compound of the
Bajrakli Mosque in downtown Belgrade on December 8, 1992, causing
damages. The mosque has been targeted seven times since 1990. The
latest attack took place last week during which the facade of the
16-century mosque was damaged.
</P>
<P>
The group was believed to have made another bombing on May 26,
1993, when Dobrilovic apparently lobbed an explosive device into
the compound of St. Anthony, a Roman Catholic Church in Belgrade,
also causing damage.
</P>
<P>
At the time of the arrest, police found 1.9 kg of explosives,
three hand grenades, three pistols, a scorpio automatic gun,
munitions and detonators at the hideout of the bombing suspects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
