<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank, IMF End Spring Meetings Fruitlessly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) concluded their week-long Spring
Meetings here today with little progress on plans for debt relief
and for avoiding financial emergencies.
</P>
<P>
In a communique, the Development Committee and the joint
ministerial committee of the World Bank and IMF voiced their
support for the findings of the Task Force on Multilateral
Development Banks (MDBs), which was established in October 1994 to
assess the implications of globalization. The Ministers believed
the MDBs have a critical role to play in support of developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
On ways to resolve debt problems of the heavily indebted poor
countries (HIPCs), Ministers welcomed a Framework for Action
presented by the Bank and IMF management. Ministers agreed that
the principal goal of the proposed framework should be to ensure,
for these HIPC countries, that adjustment and reform efforts are
not put at risk by continued high debt and debt-service burdens.
</P>
<P>
The Interim Committee of the IMF issued a communique after its
meeting on Monday. The Committee, which is regarded as the
policy-making body for the international institution, welcomed the
establishment of the Special Data Dissemination Standard for
member nations having or seeking access to international capital
markets as a way of surveillance to the new global financial
market.
</P>
<P>
The IMF committee also reiterated its support for continuation
of the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF), including
establishment of a self-sustained ESAF, as the centerpiece of the
IMF's strategy to help the low-income countries.
</P>
<P>
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus said no agreement was
reached on the key issue of expanding resources to deal with
future problems like the Mexican financial chaos.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and IMF officials have proposed that the two
world lending organizations join with rich countries to reduce the
97 billion U.S. dollars owed by 20 of the poorest countries, most
of them in Sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
A proposal to sell up to 5 percent, or 2 billion dollars of the
IMF's 40 billion dollars in gold, won some support at the
IMF-World Bank meetings, but no conclusion was reached.
</P>
<P>
The United States is the largest donor to both the World Bank
and IMF, but congressional rejection to approve proposed
contributions to international institutions has kept U.S. payments
below U.S. pledges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
