<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook Islands Announces Measures to Avert Economic Ruin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Sir Geoffrey
Henry of Cook Islands has announced sweeping spending cuts in a
bid to save the Pacific Islands from the ongoing financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Television New Zealand reported today that Sir Geoffrey
outlined an emergency plan last night aimed at heading off
economic ruin of the country.
</P>
<P>
The package included selling all state-owned enterprises,
halving the number of government departments and re-advertising
all state jobs and a short-term 50 percent pay cut for state
servants.
</P>
<P>
Sir Geoffrey said there was no alternative to the pay cuts
until the end of the current fiscal year ending June. But the cuts
would be repaid within two years.
</P>
<P>
The belt-tightening measures will also affect Cook Islands'
three representative offices abroad. Staff members in Auckland
will be cut and offices in Canberra and Sydney will be closed.
</P>
<P>
The Cook Islands, with an adult population of 10,000, now
reportedly  incurs a national debt of 100 million NZ dollars (68
million US dollars) and 25 million NZ dollars (17 million US
dollars) in defaulted loans, loan interest and money taken from
the workers' compensation fund.
</P>
<P>
The islands has asked New Zealand for financial help, but New
Zealand has turned down the request.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
