<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eurotunnel to Fight on Despite Record Company Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Eurotunnel, The Anglo-French
Channel tunnel operator, Monday unveiled losses of 925 million
pounds (1.4 billion U.S. dollars) for 1995, its first full year of
operation, one of the largest single-year deficits ever by a UK
company.
</P>
<P>
Eurotunnel has been in negotiations with its 225 banks since
September, when it suspended interest payments on 8.1 billion
pounds (12.2 billion US dollars) of debt after deciding that it
could not meet its interest payments from revenues for many years.
</P>
<P>
It said Monday that little progress had been made in the bank
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Alastair Morton, co-chairman of Erurotunnel, conceded that
there was no chance of Eurotunnel repaying its debt during the
56-year life of the operating concession.
</P>
<P>
But he said the company's financial performance was rapidly
improving, adding that Eurotunnel had grabbed almost half of the
cross-Channel market in its first year of operations and had made
it the market leader.
</P>
<P>
The company is forecasting an increase in turnover of at least
50 percent this year and costs are budgeted to be cut by 20
percent a year for three years.
</P>
<P>
An initiative to boost turnover further is expected to be
announced next month. This is likely to include a further
intensification of the price war against the ferries on duty-free
shopping at the tunnel terminals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
