<HEADLINE> U.S. White House and Congress discuss 1996 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government and
Congress discussed today the budget of fiscal 1996 and reportedly
inched closer to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
A day before a stopgap spending authority for dozens of U.S.
agencies expires, top Republicans were exploring an offer from
White House chief of staff Leon Panetta aimed at resolving the
chief remaining hurdle to a compromise, the bill's environmental
language.
</P>
<P>
Republicans met with Panetta for 80 minutes behind closed doors
at the U.S. Capitol but it was unclear whether Republicans would
accept the idea.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to narrow our differences and made significant
progress in a number of areas," Panetta told reporters after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Though the 160 billion dollars measure's final shape was still
evolving, Republican leaders said they planned to bring it to the
House floor Wednesday. The bill would finance dozens of federal
agencies for the remaining five months of fiscal 1996, and end
what has become a lingering political headache for both parties.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the bargaining said the two sides had
tentatively agreed to add about 1 billion dollars that Clinton
wanted to the legislation, including extra money for the
environment. Final details on some of the funds are still being
worked out.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. departments and agencies are operating under stopgap
spending bills in the past seven months since the U.S. fiscal year
1996 started on October 1, 1996. The present temporary spending
bill, the 12th in the fiscal year, will expire on April 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
