<HEADLINE> OAS Permanent Council Meets on Paraguay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 23 (Xinhua) -- The Permanent Council of the
Organization of American States began a special session at its
headquarters here at noon today to discuss the situation in
Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
The council meeting was requested by Paraguay's mission to the
OAS after reports from Asuncion said that the country's army
commander General Lino Cesar Oviedo has defied an order from
President Carlos Wasmosy to step down from office and has taken
refuge in an army barracks.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting is still going on," an OAS official said,
declining to give any details about the council meeting.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department issued a statement expressing
"serious concern" over the situation in Asuncion. "Any recourse to
extraconstitutional action will be completely unacceptable to the
United States," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arturo Valenzuela, deputy assistant secretary for
Inter-American Affairs at the OAS said today that the Clinton
administration has cut off military aid to Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry indicated Washington's
strong support for the government of President Carlos Wasmosy. "We
are pressing very hard to make sure that democratic rule
maintained and that constitutional norms apply," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
