<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Opposition Leader On Domestic Matters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 23 (Xinhua) -- President of Mozambique's first
opposition party Renamo, Afonso Macachomaceta Dhlakama, expressed
his view here today on domestic problems such as "financial
crisis", military troops and local elections.
</P>
<P>
Dhlakama told a news conference that all the opposition
parties are being faced with financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
His Resistencia Nacionae de Mocambique (Renamo) is striving to
set up small businesses to get out of the financial predicament,
he said, complaining that the government has placed blocks to its
businesses.
</P>
<P>
On the military issues, Dhlakama accused President Joaquin
Chissano, also Commander-in-Chief of the armed forces, of
"sending all officers from Renamo abroad with an excuse that they
need studies."
</P>
<P>
The government wants to replace them with members from the
ruling Forcas Populares de Libertacao de Mosambique (FRELIMO),
according to Dhlakama.
</P>
<P>
But he stated that his party is still ready to take part in
the forthcoming local elections, adding that the Renamo hopes the
local elections will be held in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Dhlakama disclosed that he may be able to meet President
Chissano late this month or early next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
