<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswanan Deploys Troops Near Namibia To Kill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 23 (Xinhua) -- Botswana has confirmed its
troops deployment near the disputed Kasikili Island, but
maintained it was part of an operation to destroy about 300,000
cattle infected with bovine lung sickness.
</P>
<P>
Namibian Foreign Affairs Minister Theo-Ben Gurirab said that
Botswana's High Commissioner to Namibia, Rosemary Ditlhabi
Oliphant, had confirmed the deployment of soldiers, police and
anti-poaching units near the disputed island along the border,
the South African Press Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
However, Oliphant claimed that the troop movements are
necessary as the government has decided to destroy infected
cattle.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Gurirab said Botswana military build-up near the
border was provocative, saying Namibia was not prepared to go to
war over the island.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the Botswana government said it was
"regrettable" that the Namibian government, after being
officially informed, had not told its citizens about the reasons
for the troops movements.
</P>
<P>
Both Namibia and Botswana claim ownership of the small island
in the Chobe River separating north-eastern Namibia from
Botswana.
</P>
<P>
Having failed to negotiate a settlement earlier this year,
Botswana and Namibia agreed to take the case to the International
Court of Justice at the Hague and committed themselves to abide
by the world court's ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
